|v0.1.47 |2026-05-28 |''Four small create-flow UX fixes — Reset row, Ctrl-Enter mass-create, draft re-seeding, DEL-to-unset field.'' Observed in the cascade-palette "+ New <kind>" create flow. (1) ''New Reset row.'' Each `+ New <kind>` drill now carries a ''Reset to defaults'' leaf (♻ icon in ca-icon, plain text in ca-name to avoid double-render) at `ca-order: 3` in the `Save` group with `ca-after-fire: keep` so the palette stays open. Action: delete the per-kind draft tiddler + transclude new ''`kind.force-apply-defaults`'' against the same target — restoring a clean defaults-seeded form mid-flow without walking back out. Save leaf also gained `ca-group:"Save"` (was group-less) so Save + Reset + Clone now sit clustered together at the top instead of Clone+Reset migrating below the field rows via `reorderByGroup`. ''Why a new procedure:'' `kind.apply-defaults-to` (existing) has a `:filter[<target-tid>!has<field-key>]` gate so it's idempotent for the "seed defaults if missing" callers (drill ca-actions, defensive save-time). But `<$transclude>` pre-renders its child action widgets at fire time — so the gate evaluates against the PRE-deletetiddler state. Re-clicking Reset would toggle: click 1 (draft has defaults → gate empty → no setfields → deletetiddler runs → end: empty), click 2 (draft empty → gate matches all fields → setfields pre-built → deletetiddler runs → setfields fire → end: defaults). ''Fix:'' `kind.force-apply-defaults` skips the `!has` gate — its inner filter is `[<raw-default>!is[blank]]` (just "does this field have a default defined", independent of target state). Pre-rendered setfields fire unconditionally after deletetiddler clears the draft, yielding a stable end-state on every click. Same pattern applied to creator.tid's Reset button. Shipped via new `kind.cascade-reset-draft-row` + `-build` helpers; added to `kind.cascade-fields-for-create`'s row list. (2) ''Ctrl-Enter on Save = mass-create.'' Previously Ctrl-Enter and Enter behaved identically on the Save leaf: create + delete draft + navigate. The Ctrl-Enter convention in cascade-palette is "stay open", so the form was emptied (draft deleted) but the palette stayed visible — confusing. Now Save's action branches on the new `<<keep-open>>` variable (cascade-palette 0.0.69): Ctrl-Enter ''only'' creates the tiddler — the draft stays intact so the form remains populated, and the user can Ctrl-Enter repeatedly to spawn a batch of similar instances (`$action-createtiddler` auto-uniquifies the basetitle on collision: "Name", "Name 1", "Name 2", …). Plain Enter is unchanged (create + apply-defaults defensively + delete draft + navigate). ''Refactor:'' the bulky `ca-actions` literal in `kind.save-leaf-build` (~20 chained `addsuffix` steps with `_brackets!!lb/rb` escaping for the nested `<$let>` and `{{{ }}}`) is now a single `<$transclude $variable="kind.cascade-save-instance" …/>` call. The branching logic lives in the new `\procedure kind.cascade-save-instance(kind-tid, draft-tid, type-key, keep-open)` — plain wikitext with `<%if [<keep-open>match[yes]] %>` / `<%else%>` / `<%endif%>`, much easier to read and audit. ''Hint update:'' Save's `ca-hint` now spells out the keystroke contract: "Enter creates the instance and opens it. Ctrl-Enter creates without closing or clearing the form — repeat for fast batch entry." (3) ''Draft re-seeding after single-create.'' Previously a side-effect of (2)'s old code: after Enter creates + deletes the draft, the next `+ New <kind>` drill re-fires its `ca-actions` (which transcludes `kind.apply-defaults-to` against the per-kind draft tiddler — seeded since v0.1.44). That part already worked. The visible symptom users reported — "form is cleared but defaults aren't applied anymore" — was specifically the Ctrl-Enter path where the palette stayed open without re-running the drill's ca-actions. Resolved by (2): Ctrl-Enter no longer deletes the draft, so the form stays as-is. (4) ''DEL on a field row clears the value.'' Cascade-palette 0.0.69 added a DEL handler for `ca-bind-tiddler` + `ca-bind-field` rows — kind's field-edit rows (built by `kind.text-build`, `kind.number-build`, `kind.date-build`, `kind.collection-build`) all carry that binding pair, so DEL on a focused field row now unsets the field directly (whole-field unset via action-deletefield idiom, sub-path bindings get `""`). No kind-side change needed — the binding fields were already populated, the cp engine just gained the keystroke. (5) ''In-tiddler creator's "Clear draft" button renamed to "♻ Reset to defaults"'' for consistency with the new cascade-palette Reset row label. Tooltip also slightly tightened. Same action (`$action-deletetiddler` + `kind.apply-defaults-to`). (6) ''Mass-create now navigates the new tiddler into the story river behind the palette.'' Previously Ctrl-Enter created the tiddler silently — no visual feedback. The Save procedure's `keep-open` branch now captures the post-uniquification title via `$action-createtiddler $savetitle="$:/state/rimir/kind/__last-mass-create"` and follows up with `$action-navigate` to that title. The new tiddler appears at the top of the story river (per `$:/config/Navigation/openLinkFromOutsideRiver` default) — clear "yes, it happened" cue. ''Why focus survives:'' TW's `tm-navigate` adds the title to the story list and re-renders the story river, but it doesn't call `.focus()` on the rendered tiddler frame (verified against core `navigator.js` — no `.focus()` calls). So the palette input keeps active focus and the user can immediately Ctrl-Enter again for the next instance without re-clicking. (7) ''Title-collision check now blocks save instead of silently uniquifying.'' Previously `$action-createtiddler $basetitle=<<computed>>` auto-appended " 1", " 2", … on collision — easy to accidentally spawn duplicates with Ctrl-Enter mass-create. The Save filter chain now inserts a collision check via new `kind.save-leaf-or-collision-warning` (between the existing constraint-violation gate and the actual `save-leaf-build`): if the computed title already exists as a tiddler OR shadow, emit a "Cannot save — title ‘X’ already exists" warning leaf (`ca-icon: ⛔`, `ca-after-fire: keep`, no actions — symmetric with the title-formula-empty and constraint-violation warnings already in this chain). User has to adjust a field that affects the title-formula (or rename the existing tiddler) — Save unblocks the moment the title resolves to a free name. ''Why blocking, not confirm-dialog:'' for mass-create, a confirm stage per Ctrl-Enter would mean two clicks per save (Ctrl-Enter → confirm → Ctrl-Enter → confirm → …) — defeats the whole point. Blocking preserves single-keystroke mass-create as long as each entry's title-formula actually disambiguates. Legitimate "I want a second 'TODO' tiddler" needs an explicit field change anyway. ''Implementation:'' new `kind.title-collides(title)` helper = `[<title>has[title]]` — one filter step. `has[title]` is true when the tiddler (user OR shadow — `wiki.getTiddler` checks both stores) has a `title` field, which every existing tiddler does. Yields the title if it exists anywhere, empty otherwise. ''Why this form and not the obvious `[<title>!is[missing]]`:'' `is[missing]` only checks `wiki.tiddlerExists` (user store only — shadow titles count as "missing"). Shadow collision detection would need a union with `is[shadow]`, more brittle. ''Why not `:filter[<currentTiddler>!is[missing]]`:'' inside `:filter[]`, `<currentTiddler>` resolves to the OUTER widget's currentTiddler — in cp's filter evaluation, that's the picked kind-tid (e.g. `$:/config/rimir/kind/types/person`) — NOT the iteration item. So the inner check ran against the kind-tid, not the title being tested. If the kind-tid happened to be a shadow (e.g. a model-defined type), `!is[missing]` returned empty → the filter dropped all iterations → no collision ever detected. `has[title]` works on the operator's default source (the iteration item) so it tests the right thing. New `kind.collision-warning-row-build(title)` shapes the warning row. The row's `ca-name` uses Unicode smart quotes ‘…’ around the title rather than escaped JSON double-quotes `\"…\"` — avoids brittle filter-string escaping (the escaped form silently produced unparseable JSON when filter `+[addsuffix[...]]` quoted characters interacted with TW filter's bracket rules, causing the row to drop and Save to vanish without trace). Same collision gate is wired into the parallel `+ Create new <ref-kind>` spawn flow via new `kind.spawn-save-leaf-or-collision` — same behaviour for ref-creation. (8) ''Clone row icon moved out of `ca-name`.'' The Clone-from-existing row had `📋` baked into the name string while Save / Reset put their icons in `ca-icon`. cp renders the icon slot at a fixed left-column width, so Clone's name (with the emoji counted as part of the text) started further left than its siblings — visually misaligned. Split: `ca-icon:"📋"` + `ca-name:"Clone fields from existing <caption>"`. ''Touches:'' `cascade-helpers.tid` (new `kind.cascade-reset-draft-row` + `-build`; added to `kind.cascade-fields-for-create`; refactored `kind.save-leaf-build` action wikitext; new `kind.cascade-save-instance` procedure), `creator.tid` (button label + tooltip). No JS in this plugin — but requires cascade-palette ≥ 0.0.69 for `<<keep-open>>` and DEL-to-unset. No restart needed for kind itself; cascade-palette JS changes need one. |
|v0.1.46 |2026-05-27 |''Perf: unique-constraint walks no longer scan every tiddler in the wiki on every render.'' User report: opening kind-creation OR the cp `+ New _DEFAULT` flow took >300ms on the `_default` type. Root cause: `_default`'s `aliases` field carries `unique:wiki`, which fires `kind.viol-unique-wiki` on every render of the editor (inline error display in `field-input.tid`) AND every evaluation of the Create button's `disabled` attribute (via `kind.any-invalid` aggregating all viol-* per field) — that's two walks per render. Each walk was `[all[shadows+tiddlers]]` (~2500 candidates in a typical dev wiki: ~1200 user tiddlers + ~1300 plugin shadows), iterating every candidate through `kind.same-value-of` even though only a tiny fraction carry the `aliases` field. Same cost on cp's save-leaf evaluation. ''Two-part fix:'' (1) ''Narrow the candidate set'' to tiddlers that actually have the field — `kind.dups-wiki` and `kind.dups-in-type` now prepend a `has<field-key>` filter step: `[all[shadows+tiddlers]has<field-key>]` and `[function[kind.instances-of],<type-key>has<field-key>]`. A tiddler without the field by definition has no value to share with the target, so excluding it is safe. The 2500-candidate walk for `aliases` drops to maybe 20-50 candidates (only tiddlers that actually use `aliases`), and the per-candidate `same-value-of` JSON-gets are skipped for everyone else. (2) ''Short-circuit on empty target field'' — `kind.viol-unique` and `kind.viol-unique-wiki` now insert `:filter[<target-tid>has<field-key>]` BEFORE the `:filter[function[kind.dups-*]...]` step. When the target has no value in the field (the dominant case — every fresh draft, every untouched optional field), the whole dups walk is skipped entirely. The empty draft case (initial render of creator / cp create-flow) goes from "walk all tiddlers per unique field" to "single has-field check per unique field". ''Why both:'' (1) helps the case where the user typed a value AND it's not actually a duplicate (the most common live-typing path — we still have to walk SOME candidates, but a much smaller set). (2) helps the case where the user hasn't typed anything yet (initial draft render — we skip the walk entirely). Together they cover both phases of the create flow. ''Probe verification:'' against `_default`-shaped type, empty draft now returns instantly from `viol-unique-wiki` (short-circuit fires before the walk); filled draft with `aliases:alpha` walks only the few tiddlers that have the `aliases` field. ''Correctness preserved:'' `same-value-of` already returns the sentinel `__kind-no-share__` for a candidate without the field (via `multi-result-with-sentinel`), so excluding it from the walk yields identical results. For single-card unique fields, `same-whole-value` requires the candidate's `value-of` to match, which is impossible if the candidate doesn't have the field. ''Cost:'' two TWO-character changes to `kind.dups-*` (added `has<field-key>`), two `:filter[<target-tid>has<field-key>]` inserts to `kind.viol-unique[-wiki]`. No semantic change. No JS, no restart. ''Touches:'' `engine.tid` only. |
|v0.1.45 |2026-05-27 |''Fix: constraint violations no longer let users save invalid entities — neither in the in-tiddler creator nor in cascade-palette create / spawn flows.'' Four coupled bugs: (1) ''`kind.viol-required` was broken''. The body used `:filter[<target-tid>get<field-key>is[blank]]` to detect missing-or-blank required fields. The pattern silently fails: when the target tiddler doesn't have the field set at all (the normal creation case), `get<field-key>` returns no items, so `is[blank]` has nothing to filter and the row drops — the violation was never reported. Because `kind.any-invalid` aggregates over `viol-required` + viol-min/max/unique/format, the whole "is this draft invalid" check was returning empty for the most common case (required field unfilled). The in-tiddler creator's Save button has `disabled={{{ [function[kind.any-invalid],…!is[blank]] }}}` — but with `any-invalid` always returning empty, `disabled` was always false → user could click Create even with required fields blank. ''Fix:'' switched the inner filter to `:filter[<target-tid>!has<field-key>]`. The `!has` operator returns the tiddler title when the field is either missing OR present with empty value, exactly the semantics required for "field is unset". Same fix pattern already used by `kind.apply-defaults-to` (added in v0.1.44). (2) ''Cascade-palette save flow ignored `any-invalid` entirely''. Both `kind.save-or-warn-leaf` (creator flow under `+ New <kind>`) and `kind.spawn-save-or-warn-leaf-for-draft` (spawn flow under `+ Create new <ref-kind>`) only checked `kind.eval-title` for empty title and routed to a Warning row when title was empty. Constraint violations never triggered a Warning row, never blocked Save — the Save leaf rendered as usual and `Enter` happily wrote out the invalid entity. ''Fix:'' inserted an `any-invalid` gate after the title-eval check. Creator chain: `kind.save-leaf-with-type-key` now routes through new `kind.save-leaf-or-invalid-warning(kind-tid, draft-tid, title, type-key)` — `[function[kind.any-invalid],<kind-tid>,<type-key>,<draft-tid>!is[blank]] :map[function[kind.invalid-warning-row-build],…] ~[function[kind.save-leaf-build],…]`. If any-invalid is non-empty (first violating field-key returned), emit a Warning leaf via the new `kind.invalid-warning-row-build(type-tid, draft-tid, viol-field-key)`. Otherwise fall back to the existing Save-leaf builder. Spawn chain: `kind.spawn-save-or-warn-leaf-for-draft` now routes its happy path through the parallel `kind.spawn-save-leaf-json-or-invalid` → `kind.spawn-save-leaf-json-or-invalid-with-key` chain — same any-invalid check, same Warning-row fallback, same Save-leaf builder when valid. The Warning row is shared (`kind.invalid-warning-row-build`) — its content is identical regardless of save destination. ''Warning row shape:'' `ca-name "Cannot save — constraint violation on <field-key>"`, `ca-icon "⛔"`, `ca-kind "leaf"`, `ca-order "1"`, `ca-group "Save"` (so it occupies the Save slot — visually swaps in/out as the user fills fields), `ca-hint "Field <field-key> violates a constraint (required / min / max / unique / format). Edit it via this drill, or open the validator tab for a full list. Save is blocked until all constraints are satisfied."`, NO `ca-actions` → Enter on the row is a no-op. The Warning lists only the FIRST violating field-key (returned by `any-invalid` via `+[first[]]`) — the user can see the full list via the Validator tab. ''Caption decision:'' the row uses the field-key directly (e.g. "status", "due_date") rather than the optionally-defined `kind.field-caption`. The shipped `\function kind.field-caption(type-tid, field-key) [function[kind.field-prop],…] ~[<field-key>]` has a latent quirk where the `~[<var>]` fallback doesn't substitute the function parameter inside a `\function` body — `~[[literal]]` works (verified via `kind.field-cardinality`'s `~[[single]]`) but `~[<param>]` doesn't. Existing callers like `kind.shape-text-with-typed` work around it by applying the fallback at the CALL site: `[function[kind.field-caption],…] ~[<field-key>]`. We didn't replicate that here because the field-key is fully sufficient for a warning label (it's the same identifier the user typed when defining the field, and matches what the Validator tab uses). ''Why a Warning row instead of just hiding Save:'' discoverability — the user sees something is wrong AND why, instead of wondering why Save vanished. Same UX pattern as the title-formula warning shipped in v0.1.40. ''Reactivity:'' cascade-palette re-evaluates `ca-items-from` on tiddler changes — as soon as the user fills the missing required field, any-invalid returns empty, the Warning row swaps out, the Save leaf swaps in. ''No JS, no restart.'' (3) ''Creator's `<$button disabled>` was always enabled even when `any-invalid` returned non-empty.'' TW's button widget checks `this.isDisabled === "yes"` (core `button.js:92`) — any other value (empty OR any other string like the field-key returned by `any-invalid`) is treated as "not disabled". Our pattern `disabled={{{ [function[kind.any-invalid],…!is[blank]] }}}` evaluated to the violating field-key (e.g. `"status"`) when invalid — which is not `"yes"` so the button stayed enabled. The `!is[blank]` filter step was intended to produce a truthy/empty toggle but didn't convert to the literal `"yes"` value the widget expects. ''Fix:'' append `then[yes]` after `!is[blank]` in `creator.tid`'s disabled expression — `[function[kind.any-invalid],…!is[blank]then[yes]]`. When `any-invalid` is empty, `!is[blank]` filters it out → result empty → disabled="" → button enabled. When `any-invalid` is non-empty (field-key returned), `!is[blank]` keeps it → `then[yes]` converts to `"yes"` → disabled="yes" → button disabled. The existing `kind.add-as-new-disabled` helper (line 64) already used this `then[yes]` idiom correctly — the creator's button was the outlier. (4) ''CP Warning rows closed the palette on Enter — should be no-op.'' Both warning rows (`kind.save-warning-row-build` for title-empty, `kind.invalid-warning-row-build` for constraint violation) had no `ca-actions`, but cp's default leaf behaviour is to close the palette after firing (via `fireLeafAction` → `afterAction` → `close()` when `keepOpen=false`). The user pressing Enter on a warning row ended up dismissing the palette and losing their draft context. ''Fix:'' added `"ca-after-fire":"keep"` to both warning row JSONs. cp's `fireLeafAction` (cp-firing.js:469) treats `ca-after-fire:"keep"` as forcing `keepOpen=true` → `afterAction` runs the (no-op) actions and recomputes the stage instead of closing → palette stays open, warning row stays visible, user can keep editing. Same UX pattern as preset-apply leaves that mutate state and need to stay visible. ''Touches:'' `engine.tid` (one-line fix to `kind.viol-required`), `cascade-helpers.tid` (4 new helpers + 2 warning-row additions), `creator.tid` (one-line button `disabled` expression). |
|v0.1.44 |2026-05-27 |''Big round: per-field `default` property with token expansion, multi-cardinality text fields, several latent bugs fixed.'' (1) ''New field property `default`'' — applied when creating a new instance, only fills the field if it would otherwise be blank. Two tokens are expanded at apply-time: `%TODAY%` → today at midnight in TW canonical 17-char (`YYYY0MM0DD000000000`), `%NOW%` → current moment in TW canonical 17-char. Unknown tokens (e.g. `%FOO%`) pass through as literals. Display (DD.MM.YYYY etc.) is the view layer's job — storage stays canonical so `$edit-date` and `format:date[]` keep working. (2) ''Three UI surfaces for setting `default'''': (a) ''Type-builder'' has a new `default` column between icon and constraints, dispatching on typed (enum-single → `<$select>` over options, number → number input, else → text input with `%TODAY% / %NOW%` placeholder hint); ref/`$title`/`$calculated` show N/A. (b) ''Cascade-palette type-definition flow'' (manage-kinds → field) has a new "default" entry between cardinality and constraints with the same dispatch — enum-single drills into a picker (options as leaves + "(none)" clear-leaf using `jsondelete`), others get a text-input row bound to the JSON path. (c) ''Raw JSON'' schema doc updated to list `"default"`. (3) ''Defaults are pre-applied eagerly so values are visible during editing, not only on save.'' Two surfaces: (a) ''In-tiddler creator'' — replaced the `<$select>` type picker with a pill-button row; clicking a pill sets the state AND fires `kind.apply-defaults-to` on the per-type draft. The standalone "Apply defaults" button is gone; "Clear draft" now also re-seeds. (b) ''Cascade-palette create flows'' — `kind.kind-create-build` (top-level "+ New &lt;kind&gt;") and `kind.ref-create-new-row-build` (spawn "+ Create new &lt;ref-kind&gt;") now emit `ca-actions` on the drill row that fires `kind.apply-defaults-to` against the about-to-open draft. Requires cascade-palette v0.0.66 (which extends `drillSelected` to fire `ca-actions` on drill-enter). Save-time apply-defaults remains as a safety net (idempotent + cheap). (4) ''Multi-cardinality text fields'' (extends the typed system): in-tiddler editor renders a pill row with × per entry + `<$keyboard key="Enter">`-wrapped add-input (uses `$action-listops` with `+[<v>]` / `-[<v>]` to treat values as single tokens — `$append`/`$remove` operands would split on whitespace). Cascade-palette gets a drill into a values list (each existing value as a leaf with `ca-on-delete` removing it via subfilter, plus a "+ Add value…" text-row appending via `+[<picked>]`). Display via comma-joined captions on the bound drill row. (5) ''Per-entry uniqueness for multi fields'': `viol-unique` / `viol-unique-wiki` now do per-list-entry overlap detection when cardinality is multi (any shared entry between two instances fails the check), not whole-field equality. New `viol-self-dup` flags duplicate entries within the same list (e.g. `aliases: foo foo`) when any unique constraint is set. Engine introduces a sentinel pattern (`__kind-no-share__`) to disambiguate "multi mode with no shares" from "single mode with empty value" in `kind.same-value-of`. (6) ''Fix (pre-existing): enum picker showed ALL wiki tiddlers instead of the field's options.'' `kind.collection-fn-enum-or-ref` had two unconditional `:map` runs (one for enum, one for ref); the ref branch overwrote the enum branch's output every time. Changed second branch to `~[function[kind.ref-fn-by-card],…]` else-prefix so it fires only when enum branch is empty. Affected every enum field in the cp create-entity flow, not just status. (7) ''Fix (pre-existing): datetime `$edit-date` had `format="YYYY-MM-DD HH:mm"` — `HH` is not a recognised TW format code'' (lowercase `0hh` is), so datetime values were saved with literal "HH" in place. Dropped the format attribute entirely; `$edit-date` now stores TW canonical 17-char, consistent with date fields and with `%NOW%`. (8) ''Fix: enum dispatch in cp default-row when cardinality unset.'' New helper `kind.cascade-field-card-single` returns "single" if the field's `cardinality` is missing or explicitly "single", so the enum-single → drill branch fires correctly even on legacy fields without a cardinality key. ''Touches:'' `engine.tid` (4 new helpers + `kind.apply-defaults-to` procedure + multi-cardinality viol-* updates), `type-builder.tid` (new `kind.cell-default` procedure + new column + tooltip + schema-doc), `field-input.tid` (multi-text editor + `viol-self-dup` inline error + datetime format-attr drop), `cascade-helpers.tid` (multi-text drill row builders + helper refactor for `kind.kind-create-build` / `kind.ref-create-new-row-build` to inject `ca-actions`), `palette/cascade-helpers.tid` (new default row + dispatch + picker-items + clear-row), `creator.tid` (pill-picker refactor). No JS in this plugin — but requires cascade-palette ≥ 0.0.66 + scribe ≥ 0.1.2; restart of host wiki for those JS changes. |
|v0.1.43 |2026-05-27 |''Fix: delete-kind dialog ALWAYS said "no instances exist" — instance count was broken since 0.1.39.'' Refactor in 0.1.39 collapsed two filter runs into one, breaking the count: `\function kind.kind-instance-count-for(type-key) [function[kind.instances-of],<type-key>count[]]`. The `<type-key>count[]` token sequence is ambiguous in TW filter grammar — the parser doesn't reliably split `function[X],<a>` from a subsequent `count[]` operator (no separator between the var-substitution and the operator name). Result: the function call either consumed `count[]` as a malformed second arg or applied `count[]` to `<type-key>` (treating type-key as a list of one and returning "1" for the wrong thing), and either way the downstream `[<count>!match[0]]` branch did not produce the expected non-zero count, so the safe-message fallback fired in every case — including when instances DID exist. ''Fix:'' split into the proven two-run form: `[function[kind.instances-of],<type-key>] +[count[]]`. Now Run 1 returns the instance list, Run 2 applies `+[count[]]` to the accumulator → string like "1" / "3" / "0". The 0.1.35 original was exactly this pattern (`[<kind-tid>get[kind.type]] :map:flat[function[kind.instances-of],<currentTiddler>] +[count[]]`) — the 0.1.39 type-key-threading refactor lost the `+[count[]]` separator. ''Lesson:'' when refactoring filter chains, the `+[op[]]` separator between a function call and a chained operator is essential — chaining operators directly after `<var>` without `]` `+[` boundary causes the parser to misinterpret. ''Verified by trace:'' for a kind "node" with type-key="node" and one instance with `kind.type:node !has[kind.fields]`: now `kind-instance-count-for("node")` = ["1"], `kind-delete-consequence-text("node","1")` → `[<count>!match[0]]` keeps "1" → `:map[function[kind.kind-delete-consequence-warning],"node","1"]` produces the warning text including "1 instance(s) with kind.type=\"node\"". Dialog should now display the warning. ''No JS, no restart.'' |
|v0.1.42 |2026-05-27 |''Fix: Save and Warning rows showed icon twice (💾💾 / ⛔⛔).'' v0.1.40 + v0.1.41 set BOTH `ca-icon` (e.g. `"💾"`) AND prefixed the same icon inside `ca-name` (e.g. `"💾 Save as \"<title>\""`). Cascade-palette renders rows as `<icon> <name>`, so duplication appeared. ''Fix:'' strip the icon from ca-name on three builders — `kind.save-warning-row-build` (ca-name now `"Cannot save — title-formula yields empty"`), `kind.save-leaf-build` (ca-name `"Save as \"<title>\""`), `kind.spawn-save-leaf-json` (ca-name `"Save as \"<title>\""`). All three retain `ca-icon` separately so the icon still renders, just once. ''Side fix on spawn path:'' previously `kind.spawn-save-leaf-json` had its icon inlined in ca-name (`"💾 Save"`) with no separate ca-icon field — for consistency with the creator path, it now uses ca-name `"Save as \"…\""` + `ca-icon "💾"`. ''No JS, no restart.'' |
|v0.1.41 |2026-05-27 |''Save row previews computed title in its ca-name: `💾 Save as "<title>"`.'' Follow-up to v0.1.40's Save/Warning dispatch: instead of just reading "Save", the Save leaf now embeds the computed `kind.eval-title(kind-tid, draft-tid)` result as part of its display name — e.g. `💾 Save as "test"` when caption=test resolves to "test" via the title-formula. User sees the exact title the new tiddler will get, without having to mentally apply the formula or peek inside. Combined with v0.1.40's Warning row (when title is empty), the Save row's name is now a live diagnostic: if it reads "Save as «expected»" the user knows the formula resolved correctly; if the Warning row is showing instead, they know to fix something. ''Plumbing:'' both `kind.save-or-warn-leaf` (creator) and `kind.spawn-save-or-warn-leaf-for-draft` (spawn) now pass `<currentTiddler>` (which is the iteration value = the computed title from the `[function[kind.eval-title],...!is[blank]]` step) to their downstream Save-build functions. ''Creator:'' `kind.save-leaf-with-type-key(kind-tid, draft-tid, title)` and `kind.save-leaf-build(kind-tid, draft-tid, type-key, title)` got an extra `title` arg. The build was restructured: instead of seeding the filter chain with `<kind-tid>` and growing outward (the old pattern), it now seeds with `<title>` so the title is the FIRST piece inserted into the JSON's `ca-name`. The rest of the JSON (action chain with `<<computed>>`, `$basetitle`, kind.type=..., navigate $to=...) is appended via addsuffix — using the existing `_brackets!!lb` / `!!rb` textref pattern for the `[function[kind.eval-title],[<kind-tid>],[<draft-tid>]]` filter literal inside the `<$let computed={{{ ... }}}>`. The action chain is otherwise unchanged — it still computes the title via `kind.eval-title` at fire-time, so any change between row-build and Enter is reflected in the actual created tiddler. ''Spawn:'' `kind.spawn-save-leaf-json(ref-type-tid, parent-tid, parent-field, parent-card, title)` got the same treatment — restructured to seed with `<title>`, kind-tid + parent-tid appended via addsuffix to land in the `<$transclude $variable="kind.cascade-spawn-save" parent-tid="..." …kind-tid="..."/>` action. ''ca-name vs action:'' ca-name is the row label (preview only); the action still re-evaluates `kind.eval-title` at fire-time (via the unchanged `<<computed>>` mechanism in the creator path and the unchanged `kind.cascade-spawn-save` procedure in the spawn path). So a stale ca-name preview (if cascade-palette hasn't re-rendered for some reason) doesn't lead to a wrong-titled tiddler — the action is the source of truth, ca-name is the diagnostic. ''Limitation:'' titles containing `"` characters would break the JSON when embedded in ca-name. Title-formulas in practice produce normal text (caption + suffix, name, etc.) without quotes; not worth working around for now. ''No JS, no restart.'' |
|v0.1.40 |2026-05-27 |''Disable Save when title-formula yields empty — show diagnostic warning row instead.'' Reported by user: created a new kind "node" with only a `caption` field defined, but the default `kind.title-formula` shipped by `kind.cascade-create-kind` is `[get[name]]`. Filling caption="test" still produced an instance titled `$:/state/rimir/kind/cascade-draft/node 1` instead of `test` — `kind.eval-title` returned empty (no `name` field on the draft), `$action-createtiddler $basetitle=""` fell back to template-title-with-numeric-suffix. Silent corruption: the kind has a misconfigured formula, the user has no idea, the new tiddler has a state-tid title. ''Fix:'' both creator surfaces (standard `kind.cascade-fields-for-create` AND spawn `kind.cascade-spawn-fields`) now route their Save through a new dispatcher: `kind.save-or-warn-leaf(kind-tid, draft-tid)` (creator) and `kind.spawn-save-or-warn-leaf-for-draft(ref-type-tid, parent-tid, parent-field, parent-card, draft-tid)` (spawn). Each checks `[function[kind.eval-title],<kind-tid>,<draft-tid>!is[blank]]`. If the eval-title is non-empty → emit the working Save leaf via the existing `kind.save-leaf-with-type-key` (creator) / `kind.spawn-save-leaf-json` (spawn). If empty → fall through to a Warning row via the new `kind.save-warning-row(kind-tid, draft-tid)` → `kind.save-warning-row-build`. ''Warning row:'' `ca-name: "⛔ Cannot save — title-formula yields empty"`, `ca-icon: "⛔"`, `ca-kind: "leaf"`, `ca-order: "1"` (same slot the Save leaf occupies — visually they swap in/out), `ca-hint` includes the actual formula in backticks (e.g. ''The kind's title-formula `[get[name]]` produces no value against the current draft. Fill the field(s) it references, OR edit the formula via Manage kinds → this kind → title-formula. Save is disabled until the title resolves to a non-empty value.''). The warning leaf has NO `ca-actions` so Enter on it is a no-op (cascade-palette default-close happens, but no destructive action fires). As the user fills fields, cascade-palette re-evaluates the items-from filter (reactive on tiddler change) — when eval-title resolves to non-empty, the row swaps back to Save. ''Why the `~[fallback]` pattern again:'' `:map[function[save-leaf],...]` runs zero times when input is empty, then `~[function[warning-row],...]` fires its fallback. Same pattern we already use for delete-consequence text. Cleaner than conditional `then[]` because `:map` operates on the accumulator and would otherwise call the build function with the wrong input. ''Side-by-side handling:'' the warning-row helpers are SHARED between creator and spawn flows — both call `kind.save-warning-row` because the warning content (show the broken formula) is identical regardless of save destination. Only the Save-leaf BUILDERS differ between the two surfaces. ''Edge case:'' if the kind has no `kind.title-formula` set at all, `kind.save-warning-row` falls back to `[[<no title-formula set>]]` so the warning still emits with that placeholder. ''No JS, no restart.'' Note: the existing `kind.cascade-create-kind` procedure (line 119) still ships `[get[name]]` as the default title-formula for new kinds — that's a separate concern (defaults could be smarter), but the warning system now makes the misconfiguration visible at use-time. |
|v0.1.39 |2026-05-27 |''DEL-key delete on kind rows in Manage kinds + diagnostic consequence text.'' Two coupled changes. ''(1) DEL-key:'' kind rows in the Manage kinds stage previously had no direct delete affordance — the user had to drill in, scroll to the `🗑 Delete this kind` leaf, then confirm. Now each kind row (built by `kind.cascade-manage-kind-build`) carries `ca-on-delete` + `ca-on-delete-consequence` (cp 0.0.50 protocol). DEL (or Backspace) on a focused kind row pushes the standard confirm sub-stage with the same per-kind consequence text used by the in-drill `🗑 Delete this kind` leaf — confirming fires the same `<$action-deletetiddler $tiddler="..."/><$action-sendmessage rimir-cascade-palette-open-entry entry="$:/plugins/rimir/kind/palette/entries/manage-kinds"/>` chain, so post-delete the user lands back at Manage kinds (relies on the cp 0.0.63 confirm-pop guard). ''(2) Diagnostic consequence text:'' user reported that the v0.1.35 dynamic count read "no instances" even when one existed. To help debug stale counts, the warning + safe messages now spell out the filter being used. ''Warning'' (count ≥ 1): `⚠ N instance(s) with kind.type="<type-key>" (and no kind.fields) currently exist — they will be ORPHANED on delete: …`. ''Safe'' (count = 0): `Delete this type-definition tiddler permanently. ✓ No instances with kind.type="<type-key>" (and no kind.fields) exist — safe to delete.`. The explicit `kind.type="<type-key>"` part exposes the search key the user can verify against their tiddler's actual `kind.type` field. The `(and no kind.fields)` reminds that any instance with a `kind.fields` field set (e.g. accidentally copy-pasted from a type-def) is excluded from the count — visible misfit, easy to diagnose. ''Restructured helpers:'' `kind.kind-instance-count` (now takes type-key directly via `-for` variant) + `kind.kind-delete-consequence-for-key(type-key)` + `kind.kind-delete-consequence-text(type-key, count)` + `kind.kind-delete-consequence-warning(type-key, count)` + new `kind.kind-delete-consequence-safe(type-key)`. The type-key threads through the chain so both messages can name the search key. The fallback now calls `function[kind.kind-delete-consequence-safe],<type-key>` to interpolate. ''Manage-kinds row chain extended:'' inserted `kind.cascade-manage-kind-with-icon(kind-tid, caption, icon)` between -with-caption and -build. This step computes the consequence via `kind.kind-delete-consequence` and threads it to the build. ''Build extended:'' `kind.cascade-manage-kind-build(kind-tid, caption, icon, consequence)` — additional consequence param, JSON gains `"ca-on-delete":"<$action-deletetiddler … sendmessage …/>","ca-on-delete-consequence":"<consequence>"`. ''JSON-escape gotcha during dev:'' first draft used `\\\"` (3 backslashes + quote) trying to embed `"` into the JSON value; correct pattern is `\"` (1 backslash + quote) — filter literal emits `\"` literally; JSON parser decodes `\"` → `"`. Same pattern used everywhere else in `cascade-helpers.tid` for embedded quotes in action strings. ''Requires cascade-palette ≥ 0.0.63'' (for the confirm-pop guard that lets the sendmessage actually land at Manage kinds). ''No JS, no restart.'' |
|v0.1.38 |2026-05-27 |''Clone-kind flow: collapsed three stages → two; post-commit jumps back to Manage kinds.'' Two UX fixes to the v0.1.36 clone-kind flow. ''Before:'' (Stage 1) Manage kinds → (Stage 2) source picker — each kind a `ca-kind: drill` row → (Stage 3) single text-input row "Type new kind type-key" — user navigated, Entered, typed, Entered again. Two Enters per clone, with Stage 3 being a one-row stage whose only job was to host the text input. Plus after commit the user landed at Stage 2 (the source picker), not at Stage 1 (Manage kinds — the natural landing). ''After:'' (Stage 1) Manage kinds → (Stage 2) source picker — each kind is now a ''`ca-kind: text` row'' itself. User navigates to the desired source, Enter on the source row directly enters edit mode (cascade-palette 0.0.50 behaviour: Enter on text/number/date rows enters edit mode); types the new key; ↵ commits — fires both the clone procedure AND `$action-sendmessage rimir-cascade-palette-open-entry` to land at Manage kinds. ''Why the source row as text-row works:'' the source-tid is baked into each row's `ca-on-commit` at build time, so each source row carries its own `<$transclude $variable="kind.cascade-clone-kind" source-tid="..." key=<<picked>>/>` with the source-tid pre-resolved. `<<picked>>` substitutes to the typed value (TW convention). Selecting a row = selecting the source; typing into it = providing the new key. ''Post-commit landing:'' cascade-palette's `exitEditMode` (cp-firing.js:379) fires `ca-on-commit`, then `recomputeStage(this.topStage())`. Our `$action-sendmessage` (chained after the clone procedure) calls `openPaletteAtEntry` which rebuilds the stack to `[root, manage-kinds]`. By the time `recomputeStage` runs, `topStage()` IS manage-kinds — so the recompute hits manage-kinds (now containing the just-cloned kind). End state: palette at Manage kinds, new kind visible in the list. ''Removed:'' `kind.cascade-clone-kind-key-input` (now unused — the dedicated key-input stage is gone). ''Touches:'' `palette/cascade-helpers.tid` (`kind.cascade-clone-kind-source-row-build` rewrite, helper removal). Requires cascade-palette ≥ 0.0.50 (Enter-on-text-row → edit mode). ''No JS, no restart.'' |
|v0.1.37 |2026-05-27 |''After confirmed delete-kind, re-open the palette at Manage kinds instead of closing.'' Confirming the `🗑 Delete this kind` leaf previously deleted the type-def and closed the palette (default leaf behaviour). The natural follow-up from "I just deleted Customer" is "now let me see my remaining kinds" — closing the palette forced the user to re-trigger `Ctrl-Space k` to get back. ''Fix:'' `kind.cascade-delete-kind-row-build` now appends a second action widget to the leaf's `ca-actions`: `<$action-sendmessage $message="rimir-cascade-palette-open-entry" entry="$:/plugins/rimir/kind/palette/entries/manage-kinds"/>` after the `$action-deletetiddler`. ''Why this works with the default close-on-fire:'' cascade-palette's `afterAction` (cp-firing.js:469) calls `this.close()` BEFORE invoking the action chain — so by the time both action widgets fire, the palette is already closed; the `$action-sendmessage` then triggers `_openEntryHandler` which calls `openPaletteAtEntry("…manage-kinds")` → `openPalette()` resets the stack and drills into the Manage kinds entry. End state: palette is open and on the Manage kinds stage, with the just-deleted kind no longer in the list (because the kind-list `kind.cascade-manage-kinds-items` re-evaluates from `kind.types-all`). ''Why not `ca-after-fire: pop`:'' the delete leaf sits two stages below Manage kinds (confirm sub-stage → kind drill stage → Manage kinds stage), and `pop` only pops once — would leave the user on the now-stale kind drill (showing a kind that no longer exists). The OPEN_ENTRY_MESSAGE pattern jumps directly to the entry rather than walking the stack. ''Reuses 0.1.29's wiring:'' the `k` leader and the `OPEN_ENTRY_MESSAGE`-handler-resets-cp-to-root behaviour shipped with cascade-palette 0.0.54 / kind 0.1.29 — this leaf just leverages the same plumbing. ''Cost:'' one extra action widget in the JSON. ''No JS, no restart.'' |
|v0.1.36 |2026-05-27 |''Layer B: clone an existing kind to seed a new kind (Manage kinds → + Clone existing kind…).'' Companion to v0.1.34's Layer A (instance cloning). Manage-kinds stage previously offered only `+ Create new kind…` (blank). Now adds `+ Clone existing kind…` (order 1001, group Kind Actions, 📋). ''Three-stage flow:'' (1) drill into clone row → source picker showing every existing kind as a drill (`kind.cascade-clone-kind-source-items` over `kind.types-all`); (2) drill into a source kind → single text-input row "Type new kind type-key…" (🔑, built by `kind.cascade-clone-kind-key-input(kind-tid)` — the kind-tid is baked into the row's ca-on-commit via the bracket-textref pattern); (3) type the new key + ↵ → fires `kind.cascade-clone-kind(source-tid, key)`. ''Clone semantics:'' `$action-createtiddler $basetitle=[[$:/config/rimir/kind/types/<key>]] $template=<<source-tid>> kind.type=<<key>> kind.caption="" kind.icon="" type="text/vnd.tiddlywiki"` — copies all source fields (kind.fields, kind.title-formula, kind.stream-fields, kind.namespaces, text, tags, …) then overrides kind.type to the new key and clears kind.caption + kind.icon so the user fills them in next. ''Why clear caption + icon but not namespaces:'' kind.type is the identity (must be unique — auto-overwritten with the typed key); kind.caption + kind.icon are display identity (semantically per-kind; clearing forces the user to pick a new value); kind.namespaces is organisational (cloning often happens within the same namespace — keeping the source's value is more often right than wrong, easy to clear after if not). ''Stage 2 row rendering:'' uses the existing caption/icon resolution pattern (`...-source-row-with-icon` → `...-build`); each row's `ca-next-title` reads "Clone from <Caption>" so the breadcrumb shows the source clearly. ''Stage 3 hint:'' explains what gets copied vs cleared — gives the user a fair warning before commit. ''No new `<<picked>>` handling needed:'' cascade-palette substitutes `<<picked>>` in text-row `ca-on-commit` to the typed value (existing 0.0.22 behaviour). ''Empty key guard:'' the procedure's `<$list filter="[<key>!is[blank]]">` no-ops on blank input (consistent with `kind.cascade-create-kind`). ''Why three stages not one or two:'' fewer stages would require encoding both "pick source" + "type new key" into a single decision; cascade-palette text rows don't drill forward after commit. Three stages keep each decision atomic, the breadcrumb readable, and Esc-back behavioural at each step. ''Filter-literal gotcha avoided:'' the clone-kind-row's `ca-items-from` value contains `[function[X]]` which has `]` chars that would prematurely close a `[[…]]` filter literal; works around via the `+[addsuffix{$:/plugins/rimir/kind/_brackets!!lb}]` + `…!!rb` chain (same pattern used by `kind.cascade-add-from-library-row` and friends). ''No JS, no restart'' — five new functions + one procedure in `palette/cascade-helpers.tid`, plus one helper-call appended to `kind.cascade-manage-kinds-items`. |
|v0.1.35 |2026-05-27 |''Delete-kind confirm dialog now shows live instance count.'' The `🗑 Delete this kind` row in the ''Manage kinds → kind drill'' (already shipped, in danger group, with `ca-confirm: yes` from earlier work) had a static `ca-confirm-consequence` reading "Existing instances are NOT touched" — true but not actionable. The user often needs to know whether deleting a kind would orphan instances before proceeding. Consequence text is now computed per-row via the new `kind.kind-delete-consequence` chain: `kind.kind-instance-count(kind-tid)` walks `[<kind-tid>get[kind.type]] :map:flat[function[kind.instances-of],<currentTiddler>] +[count[]]` to produce the count, then `kind.kind-delete-consequence-text(count)` branches via `[<count>!match[0]] :map[function[kind.kind-delete-consequence-warning],<currentTiddler>] ~[[…safe to delete…]]` — non-zero counts route through `kind.kind-delete-consequence-warning(count)` which builds the warning string by `addsuffix`-chaining; zero falls through to the safe-message via the `~` fallback. ''Two distinct messages:'' (a) zero instances → ''"Delete this type-definition tiddler permanently. ✓ No instances of this kind currently exist — safe to delete."''; (b) N instances → ''"⚠ N instance(s) of this kind currently exist — they will be ORPHANED on delete: each instance keeps its kind.type field but the schema is gone, so cascade flows / validator / creator will no longer recognise them. Delete this type-definition tiddler anyway?"''. ''Why the `~[fallback]` pattern instead of conditional `then[]`s:'' an earlier draft tried `[<count>match[0]then[zero text]] [<count>!match[0]] :map[function[warning],<currentTiddler>]` but TW filter run-prefixes operate on the accumulator from previous runs — the `:map` would then iterate the zero-text from run 1 alongside the count from run 2, calling `warning("zero text…")` and producing garbage. The fallback pattern is cleaner: only the count routes through `:map`, fallback emits when filter chain produces empty. ''Cascade-palette `ca-confirm` already does the rest:'' Enter on the delete row pushes a confirm/cancel sub-stage where the consequence text shows in the detail drawer (cascade-palette ≥ 0.0.22). User reads count, picks Cancel to back out or Confirm to delete. Existing kind-builder tab is unaffected — this only changes the cascade-palette flow. ''Row builder split:'' new `kind.cascade-delete-kind-row-build(target-tid, consequence)` does the JSON assembly; the public `kind.cascade-delete-kind-row(target-tid)` now wraps it via `:map` over the consequence chain. ''Note:'' the delete itself remains "tiddler-removal only" — orphaned instances are still not auto-cleaned. A "delete instances too" leaf would be a future addition; not in scope here. ''No JS, no restart'' — four new functions + a builder split in `palette/cascade-helpers.tid`. |
|v0.1.34 |2026-05-27 |''Clone-from-existing in cascade creator flows (Layer A of the templating idea).'' Both the standard ''Create new entity'' flow (`kind.cascade-fields-for-create`) and the in-ref-picker ''+ Create new <type>'' spawn flow (`kind.cascade-spawn-fields` from v0.1.33) now show a ''📋 Clone fields from existing <type>'' drill row (order 2, group `Save`) above the field-edit rows. Drilling lists every existing instance of the target kind via `kind.clone-source-items` → `kind.instances-of`; each instance is a `ca-kind: leaf` with `ca-after-fire: pop` and `ca-actions` that calls the new procedure ''`kind.cascade-clone-into-draft(source-tid, draft-tid, type-tid)`''. The procedure iterates `kind.field-keys` and copies each value from source to draft, skipping (a) computed fields ($title / $calculated — detected via `kind.is-computed-typed`), and (b) fields whose schema sets `clone: skip` (read via `kind.field-prop(type-tid, field-key, [clone])` — default behaviour when the prop is absent is to clone). An additional `[<source-tid>has<field-key>]` guard prevents overwriting the draft with blanks when the source has no value for a given field. After firing, `ca-after-fire: pop` returns the user to the spawn-create / creator stage with all cloneable fields pre-populated; they can then edit anything that needs adjusting (e.g. today's date overriding the cloned date, the blank `text` body if `clone: skip` was set on it for journal entries) and hit Save normally. ''Row visibility:'' the clone row only emits when at least one instance of the target kind already exists (`kind.kind-has-instances` guard — drilling into an empty picker would be confusing); first-ever instance of a kind continues to show only the field rows + Save. ''Per-field opt-out:'' `kind.fields[].clone: "skip"` excludes the field from the clone copy — currently set by editing `kind.fields` JSON directly (no cascade UI for this prop yet). Default = copy. ''Transitive composition:'' the clone procedure operates against `<<draft-tid>>` — which for the spawn flow is `kind.cascade-spawn-draft-tid(parent-tid, parent-field, ref-type-key)` and for the creator is `kind.cascade-draft-tid(kind-tid)`. So cloning at any nesting level of a multi-level spawn cascades correctly: the source picker for a level-N draft pulls instances of the level-N ref-type, and the copied values land on the level-N draft (not the level-1 one). ''No conflict with `+ Create new`'' — both rows coexist; the user picks whichever path they want. ''Common use-cases enabled by this single primitive:'' (a) clone yesterday's journal entry (location + weather sticky, `text` field marked `clone: skip` so it's blanked for the new entry); (b) clone an existing Person to create another with the same team / role pre-filled; (c) in a multi-step spawn, clone a partial sibling at each level. ''No JS, no restart'' — five new functions + one procedure in `cascade-helpers.tid`. Note: Layer B (clone a kind to seed a new kind's schema — `kind.fields` / `kind.title-formula` / `kind.stream-fields`) is a separate flow over the kind type-definitions; not part of this version. |
|v0.1.33 |2026-05-27 |''In-cascade `+ Create new <type>` rows in ref-field pickers — nested spawn flow with breadcrumb via the cascade stage stack.'' Ref-field pickers (single-select via `kind.ref-leaf-items` and multi-select via `kind.ref-toggle-items`) previously only listed EXISTING candidates of the allowed ref-type(s) — to link a brand-new instance, the user had to bail out of the current Edit-fields flow, run the Creator on the target kind, then return and re-pick the just-created instance in the original ref picker. Now both picker variants ALSO emit one `+ Create new <type-caption>` row per allowed ref-type (built by new helpers `kind.ref-create-new-items` → `kind.ref-create-new-row` → `…-with-meta` → `…-with-icon` → `…-build`). Each row is a `ca-kind: drill` whose `ca-items-from` calls a new `kind.cascade-spawn-fields(ref-type-tid, parent-tid, parent-field, parent-card)` — the four args are baked into the JSON at row-build time using the `_brackets!!lb` / `_brackets!!rb` textref pattern so the spawn target is preserved across the drill. ''Spawn-create stage'' emits a `Save` leaf at the top (new `kind.spawn-save-leaf-json`) plus the full field-edit items for a per-spawn draft tiddler (new `kind.spawn-field-edit-items` over a new `kind.cascade-spawn-draft-tid(parent-tid, parent-field, ref-type-key)` keyed by all three so multi-level spawns don't clash). The Save leaf has `ca-after-fire: pop` and fires a new procedure ''`kind.cascade-spawn-save(parent-tid, parent-field, parent-card, kind-tid)`'' which: (1) `$action-createtiddler $basetitle={{{[function[kind.eval-title],<kind-tid>,<draft-tid>]}}} $template=<<draft-tid>> $savetitle="$:/state/rimir/kind/__spawn-result" kind.type=<<kind-type-key>>` materialises the new instance with the computed title; (2) `$action-listops $subfilter="+[append{$:/state/rimir/kind/__spawn-result}]"` (parent-card=multi) or `"[{$:/state/rimir/kind/__spawn-result}]"` (parent-card=single — replaces the field) wires the new title into the parent's field; the subfilter textref reads at filter-eval time so the value `$savetitle` just wrote is picked up reliably; (3) `$action-deletetiddler <<draft-tid>>` cleans up. After firing, `ca-after-fire: pop` pops the spawn-create stage and returns the user to the ref picker — the picker re-runs `kind.ref-candidates` and now lists the just-spawned instance, AND the parent's field is already set (visible via the bound display on the picker row). ''Transitive composition via cascade itself:'' the spawn-create stage's `kind.spawn-field-edit-items` reuses `kind.field-edit-items` against the spawn draft — so any ref field of the spawned type goes through the SAME `kind.ref-leaf-items`/`kind.ref-toggle-items` which emit the same `+ Create new` rows. Drilling into one of those pushes ANOTHER spawn-create stage onto cascade-palette's stack, with its own draft (`spawn-draft/<level-N-draft-tid>/<nested-field>/<nested-ref-type>`). N levels deep is supported with zero new machinery; cascade-palette's existing breadcrumb at the top of the popup IS the spawn-stack visualiser. Each level's draft persists across back-out (cascade-palette keeps stage state on Esc — same as `kind.cascade-draft-tid` does for the standard Creator), so the user can pop back, work elsewhere, and re-drill to resume. ''No JS, no restart'' — purely new wikitext helpers + one procedure in `cascade-helpers.tid`. Builds on the existing cascade-palette `ca-after-fire: pop` mechanic shipped in cp 0.0.x and the `kind.field-edit-items` engine that already drives the Creator. |
|v0.1.32 |2026-05-26 |''Rename a field's key in the cascade.'' Closes a gap: field key was previously baked at creation and never editable from the cascade — to rename, the user had to drop to the type-builder tab or edit the JSON by hand. New ''key'' row (🔑, order 5 — sits ABOVE typed at order 10) in every field's edit substage, bound to `kind.fields[<idx>].key` via `ca-bind-path: <idx>,key`. Space → type → ↵ commits the new key; `ca-on-commit` then fires the new `\procedure kind.cascade-rename-field-key(target-tid, idx, old-key)` which auto-syncs `kind.stream-fields` (the inline-bar key list): if `old-key` was listed there, listops removes it and appends `new-key`. The sync is conditional — if `old-key` wasn't listed, the new key isn't silently added, preserving the user's stream-fields curation. Blank commit and no-change commit are both no-ops. ''What does NOT migrate:'' (a) existing instance tiddlers keep their field values under the OLD key (orphaned — visible to filters but not to the new schema), (b) references to the old key in `kind.title-formula`, in other filters, or in wikitext break and must be updated by hand. The row's hint surfaces both gotchas. ''Why no auto-migration of instance values:'' moving a field across N existing instances would be an expensive write storm and irreversible; opt-in via a follow-up "Migrate instances" leaf is cleaner than implicit behaviour. New helpers: `kind.cascade-field-key-row`, `kind.cascade-field-key-row-build`. New procedure: `kind.cascade-rename-field-key`. Tiddler-only — no restart. |
|v0.1.31 |2026-05-26 |''Reorder kind fields via Ctrl-↑ / Ctrl-↓ in the cascade.'' Field row order in the Manage-kinds drill IS the form field order (via `kind.field-keys` → `jsonindexes[]`), so reordering `kind.fields` propagates to (a) the side-preview create form, (b) instances created after the move, (c) the validator's per-field iteration order. New protocol fields `ca-on-move-up` / `ca-on-move-down` (shipped in ''cascade-palette 0.0.57'') are now emitted on every field row in `kind.cascade-field-row-build` — both transclude a new `\procedure kind.cascade-move-field(target-tid, idx, dir)` that swaps `kind.fields[idx]` with `kind.fields[idx+dir]` via two chained `jsonset:json` calls (using `jsonextract<idx>` to grab each element as a JSON object, then setting them at swapped positions). ''Bounds:'' a `<$list>` guards `0 <= other-idx < count` via `compare:integer:gteq[0]` + `+[!compare:integer:gteq<count>]` — Ctrl-↑ on the top row and Ctrl-↓ on the bottom row are silent no-ops; cp's pre-bumped selectedIndex stays clamped within the unchanged stage. ''Stream-fields unaffected:'' `kind.stream-fields` is a separate, curated ordering for the inline bar — moving a field in `kind.fields` does NOT also reorder it in `kind.stream-fields` (use the dedicated text-edit row for that). ''Gesture choice:'' Ctrl-↑/↓ rather than Alt or Shift — Ctrl is already the cascade's preview-detail modifier and the magnitude modifier on number/date rows; reusing it for "move with arrows" keeps modifier-meaning consistent (Ctrl = "do the heavy version"). Bare ↑/↓ still nudge selection. ''Surface:'' works on the same field-row drill the schema editor uses — drill into a kind, focus a field row, Ctrl-↑/Ctrl-↓. The side preview form re-renders live (via the 0.0.56 reactive refresh path) so the user sees the reordered form immediately. Requires cascade-palette ≥ 0.0.57. Tiddler-only — no restart. |
|v0.1.30 |2026-05-26 |''Live create-form preview while editing a kind in the cascade.'' Drilling into a kind (Node, Person, Task, …) in the ''Manage kinds'' cascade now splits the popup 50/50 — the left column stays the schema editor (fields, metadata, delete) and the right column renders a live create-instance form for that kind. As the user adds/removes fields, changes `typed`, edits the `kind.title-formula`, tweaks `kind.caption` / `kind.icon`, etc., the side pane re-renders so the form mirrors the live schema. ''Wiring:'' uses the side-preview protocol introduced in ''cascade-palette 0.0.52'' — `kind.cascade-manage-kind-build` now emits two extra JSON fields on each per-kind drill row: `ca-preview-template: $:/plugins/rimir/kind/palette/preview/kind-form` and `ca-preview-title: Create form preview`. Default `ca-preview-context` (`<<picked>>`) carries the kind-tid into the template. ''Template'' (new `palette/preview/kind-form.tid`) takes the type-def tiddler as `<<currentTiddler>>`, derives `type-key` via `[get[kind.type]]`, allocates a per-kind preview-draft tiddler at `$:/state/rimir/kind/cascade-preview-draft/<type-key>` (each kind gets its own preview draft — switching kinds keeps each preview's in-progress values), and `$transclude`s the shared `$:/plugins/rimir/kind/editor` exactly the way `creator.tid` does (same two-column form, same field-input dispatch, same engine-import). Computed-title hint at the bottom uses `kind.eval-title` against the preview draft so the user sees what the formula resolves to as they edit it. ''Re-render trigger:'' the cp side-preview cache is keyed by (depth, context-tiddler, template) and invalidated by the wiki change hook on those two tiddlers; editing the kind type-def via any cascade row mutates the kind-tid → cache invalidates → form re-renders. ''Interactive form:'' the user can ALSO type values directly into the preview's input widgets — those values land on the per-kind preview-draft and persist across drill-in/out (until the user pops back to the kinds list, which clears the cache but not the draft tiddler — so re-drilling restores the values). Use it as a scratch-pad to feel out the form before committing to an actual create flow. ''No JS, no restart'' — tiddler-only, plus the JS engine work already shipped in cp 0.0.56. Requires cascade-palette ≥ 0.0.52. |
|v0.1.29 |2026-05-26 |''`k` leader: drill straight into Manage kinds.'' New leader tiddler `palette/leaders/manage-kinds.tid` (`ca-leader-key: k`) fires `<$action-sendmessage $message="rimir-cascade-palette-open-entry" entry="$:/plugins/rimir/kind/palette/entries/manage-kinds"/>` — single keystroke after Ctrl-Space drops the user into the Manage-kinds drill (list of kinds + "+ Create new kind" row), skipping the find-the-entry step at the root. Reuses the new `OPEN_ENTRY_MESSAGE` shipped in ''cascade-palette 0.0.54''. Works from any cp state — the message handler resets cp to root then drills. ''Why a leader rather than a plain entry shortcut:'' the leader subsystem already handles the after-Ctrl-Space key gesture + the pill row on the cp surface, so this re-uses existing UX. ''Listed in pill row:'' the leader's `ca-leader-name`/`ca-leader-hint`/`ca-leader-help` show up in the leader pill row + detail pane, so the gesture is discoverable. Requires cascade-palette ≥ 0.0.54 for the `OPEN_ENTRY_MESSAGE` handler. Tiddler-only on the kind side. |
|v0.1.28 |2026-05-26 |''Cross-link from instance → kind schema editor.'' New entity action `actions/edit-kind-schema.tid` (`ca-entity-type: kind-entity`, 🧰, order 60 — between Edit fields and Delete) drills directly into the type-def's Manage-kinds stage from any kind-typed instance, skipping the Ctrl-Space → Manage kinds → find-the-right-kind detour. ''How:'' the action's `ca-items-from` calls a new helper `kind.cascade-edit-kind-schema-items(entity-tid)` which (1) reads the entity's `kind.type` field, (2) resolves to its type-def tiddler via `kind.locate-type`, (3) emits the same edit rows the Manage-kinds drill uses via `kind.cascade-kind-edit-items`. The middle `:map`/`:map:flat` distinction is deliberate — `locate-type` returns one type-tid per kind.type input so plain `:map` works, but `cascade-kind-edit-items` returns N rows per type-tid so the second hop needs `:map:flat` (per the [[tw-gotchas-filters#`:map` returns only the FIRST]] gotcha). ''Surface:'' any cp flow that exposes kind-entity instances (Find entity, Find by kind → kind → instances) now offers Edit kind schema in the action menu; Right-arrow → ↓ to Edit kind schema → Enter drops into the schema editor for that exact kind, no detour. Symmetric with the existing Open / Edit fields / Delete kind-entity actions. ''Edge:'' if the entity has no `kind.type` or the type-def doesn't exist, the drill returns nothing (empty stage); the action menu doesn't pre-filter for this — the row is offered for any kind-entity, which is fine because the actual kind-entity entity-type marker is only set on stages that legitimately have kind.type instances. Tiddler-only — no restart. |
|v0.1.27 |2026-05-26 |''Fix: `:map[X]` silently drops every result past index 0; cross-kind option pool was returning ~1 value instead of N.'' Looking at TW core's `filterrunprefixes/map.js:33` — without the `:flat` suffix, `:map[X]` pushes ONLY `filtered[0]||""` per iteration: the FIRST result of the inner filter, or empty string if it returned nothing. So when `:map` calls a function that returns multiple titles per iteration, all but the first are lost. ''Impact in the options picker:'' four cascade points each lost their tails — `kind.cascade-field-options-picker-items` :map'd `cascade-options-picker-with-key` (5 toggles + add-row → kept only first toggle), `kind.options-from-all-kinds` :map'd `options-from-kind` per kind (multi-option fields → kept only first option per kind), `kind.options-from-common-fields` :map'd `cf-options-at-cf-tid` per common-field (multi-option defs → kept only first option per cf), `kind.options-from-kind` :map'd `options-at-idx` per field-idx (multi-option arrays → kept only first option per idx). End result: pool collapsed to 1-2 values and the add-row was always dropped (because the function returned multiple items and only the first toggle survived). ''Fix:'' all four call sites switched to `:map:flat[function[NAME],...]` which iterates `$tw.utils.each(filtered, …)` instead of `filtered[0]`. With `:flat`, every result from each iteration's inner filter is appended. Pool now correctly produces the full union; add-row now reaches cascade-palette. ''Lesson:'' use `:map:flat` whenever the inner filter (typically a `function[NAME]` call) returns more than one value per input — which is most cases when wrapping multi-result helpers. `:map` (no flat) is the right default ONLY when the inner filter is guaranteed to emit exactly one value per input (e.g., simple value extractors `:map[get[caption]]`). Tiddler-only — no restart. |
|v0.1.26 |2026-05-25 |''Fix: enum options picker now also includes library common-field options + filters blanks.'' Two fixes to 0.1.25's cross-kind option pool. ''(a) Common-fields integration:'' the pool was only walking `kind.types-all` (user-defined kinds) — the shadow common-field tiddlers tagged `$:/tags/rimir/kind/common-field` were ignored. So `task.status` (an enum) ignored the canonical `["open","active","done","archived"]` defined on `$:/plugins/rimir/kind/common-fields/status` even though that's the ship-with canonical set. ''Fix:'' added `kind.options-from-common-fields(field-key)` that iterates `kind.common-fields-all`, filters via `kind.cf-matches-enum-key` (matches def's key + typed=enum), and emits the def's options array via `kind.cf-options-at-cf-tid`. Pool now unions across-kinds AND common-fields. ''(b) Blank values pollution:'' `+[unique[]sort[]]` deduped but didn't filter empty values — if any source kind had an empty-string option (manual JSON edit, old serialization quirk, etc.) the pool would emit an unnamed toggle. ''Fix:'' switched the final pool reduce to `+[!is[blank]unique[]sort[]]`. ''Refactor:'' renamed `kind.options-pool`'s direct kind-walk to `kind.options-from-all-kinds` for parallelism with `kind.options-from-common-fields`. ''Example after fix:'' add a fresh `status` enum field to any kind — picker immediately shows `active`, `archived`, `done`, `open` as OFF toggles (from the common-fields canonical set) + "+ Add new option…" — toggle any on to populate this field's `options` without typing. Same applies to `priority` (`low`, `medium`, `high`) and any future common-field with enum + options. Tiddler-only — no restart. |
|v0.1.25 |2026-05-25 |''Cross-kind option pool for enum picker.'' Options picker now suggests every option ever used on a same-named enum field across all kinds, not just the ones currently set on this field. Pool computed by `kind.options-pool(field-key)`: walks `kind.types-all`, for each kind iterates its `kind.fields` indices, filters to those whose `key` matches the current field-key AND whose `typed` is `enum`, collects each matching field's `options` values, then `+[unique[]sort[]]`. Each pool value becomes a toggle row — cascade-palette's existing toggle widget renders it ON if the value is in THIS field's `options` array, OFF otherwise (same mechanic ref-types uses). User can toggle pool members on/off without re-typing them; "+ Add new option…" still appends a fresh option that automatically joins the pool for that field-key in other kinds. ''Example:'' kind `task` has field `priority` with options `["low","high"]`; kind `meeting` adds field `priority` (enum); picker on meeting.priority shows `low` + `high` as OFF toggles + "+ Add new option…" — toggle them on without typing. ''New helpers:'' `kind.cascade-options-picker-with-key` (intermediate to thread field-key), `kind.options-pool`, `kind.options-from-kind`, `kind.field-matches-enum-key`, `kind.options-at-idx`. Picker entry now resolves field-key first (`jsonget<field-idx>,[key]` with `~[[]]` fallback so blank-key fields still get the add-option row). ''Why no special-case for ad-hoc empty pool:'' a brand-new enum field's pool may be empty (no other kind has a same-named enum field yet) — that's fine, picker just shows the add-row and the first option entered seeds the pool for future same-named fields. Cross-kind pooling is name-based; renaming a field changes which pool it draws from. Tiddler-only — no restart. |
|v0.1.24 |2026-05-25 |''Multi-pick sub-stage for enum options + shared array-append helper.'' Enum `options` previously was a flat text-edit row binding the whole array via `ca-bind-type: application/x-string-array` (one space-separated string the user re-typed wholesale). Now it's a drill into a picker that lists each existing option as a toggle row (toggle off = remove that option from the array) plus a "+ Add new option…" text row at the bottom that appends a new value via a shared procedure. Same UX shape as the constraints picker — Space drills, options become individually toggleable, new ones added one-at-a-time with dedup. ''Refactor:'' `kind.cascade-append-constraint` is gone — its body now lives in the generic `kind.cascade-append-array-value(target-tid, idx, prop, value)` procedure (one extra `prop` parameter threaded into `jsonindexes<idx>,<prop>` / `jsonget<idx>,<prop>,<currentTiddler>` / `jsonset:json<idx>,<prop>,<new-array>`). Custom-constraint row and add-option row both transclude the generic helper, passing `prop="constraints"` or `prop="options"`. No code duplication — same dedup-via-unique + quote-string + join + wrap-array + empty-array-fallback pipeline serves both. Dead helper `kind.cascade-field-array-prop-row` (the old wholesale text-edit array binder) removed — last caller was the old options-row. New helpers: `kind.cascade-field-options-picker-items`, `kind.cascade-field-add-option-row`. ''ref-types'' already drilled into a multi-pick picker (all kind types as toggles since 0.1.11) — no change. Tiddler-only — no restart. |
|v0.1.23 |2026-05-25 |''Fix: min/max constraint write was still buggy in 0.1.22 — subtract-of-existing didn't fire, validity filter let everything through.'' Two more bugs in the min/max constraint path. ''(a) `-[prefix<prefix>]` didn't subtract:'' the run-prefix-`-` semantics: subtract the INNER run's output from the accumulator. The inner expression `[prefix<prefix>]` has no explicit input source — TW filter parser then uses the default source (all tiddlers + shadows) rather than the accumulator, so `prefix<prefix>` returned wiki titles starting with "min:" (typically none), and subtract removed nothing. Works fine when the inner is a literal value (`-[<del-idx>]` in `kind.rebuilt-fields-without`) because that emits the variable's value directly without needing a source. ''Fix:'' switched to `:filter[<currentTiddler>!prefix<prefix>]` — `:filter` iterates the accumulator setting `<currentTiddler>` per item, so the predicate operates on each constraint value individually. Now `"5"` correctly replaces `"min:3"` with `"min:5"` (no leftover). ''(b) `compare:integer:gteq[0]` accepted "abc":'' TW's `parseInt("abc")` returns `NaN`. The compare gtFn returns `0` (default branch, NaN <-> NaN comparisons all false), `gteq` treats `r===0` as true. So `"abc" compare:integer:gteq[0]` evaluates to TRUE — non-numeric input passed the validity filter and reached the rewrite as `"min:abc"`. Conversely the previous fix `[<value>match[]]` for the blank case relied on `<value>` substitution producing `[""]` for empty value, but TW substitutes empty variables to NO INPUT (not empty string) — so `match[]` had no source and blank input was REJECTED. ''Fix:'' switched to `[<value>] ~[[]] +[is[blank]] [<value>regexp{$:/plugins/rimir/kind/_patterns!!digits}] +[first[]]` — the `~[[]]` fallback explicitly provides empty string as a result when `<value>` substitutes nothing, then `+[is[blank]]` keeps it (clear semantics); separately `[<value>regexp{...digits}]` adds the value if it matches `^[0-9]+$`; `+[first[]]` coalesces. Non-numeric / non-blank input produces no filter result → list doesn't iterate → action skipped → existing constraint stays. New `digits` pattern added to `_patterns.tid` (referenced via textref so the `[0-9]` character class doesn't break filter parsing — same trick as 0.1.21's email/phone patterns). ''Lessons:'' (1) `-[op<arg>]` only subtracts correctly when the inner is a value-emission (literal / variable); for operator-based subtraction use `:filter[<currentTiddler>!op<arg>]` to bind the accumulator as input. (2) `<v>` substitution with empty value produces no filter input — use `~[[]]` fallback explicitly. (3) `compare:integer` treats NaN as equal-to-anything (returns 0 from gtFn); never trust it for numeric input validation — use `regexp` with a stored pattern instead. Tiddler-only — no restart. |
|v0.1.22 |2026-05-25 |''Fix: setting min/max constraint via cascade prefixed all existing constraints, not just the new one.'' Two related bugs in `kind.computed-constraints-with-valid-picked` + `kind.cascade-set-constraint-num`. ''(a) Chain-prefix bug:'' the new-entry branch was written as `[<valid-picked>!is[blank]] +[addprefix<prefix>]` — two separate filter runs. The first accumulated `picked` ("3") onto the already-filtered list ("required"), giving ["required", "3"]. The `+[addprefix<prefix>]` then operated on the FULL accumulator (TW filter `+` prefix = "pipe accumulator through op"), prepending "min:" to BOTH entries → ["min:required", "min:3"]. If the user (mis-)typed the full prefixed form like "min:3" thinking they had to retype the label, the result included a "min:min:3" entry. ''Fix:'' inlined `addprefix<prefix>` into the same operator chain as the new-entry emit: `[<valid-picked>!is[blank]addprefix<prefix>]`. Now the prefix is only applied to the new entry, not the entire accumulator. ''(b) Regex validity guard didn't validate:'' the procedure's outer `<$list filter="[<value>regexp[^[0-9]*$]]">` tried to reject non-digit input but the pattern `^[0-9]*$` contains a `]` inside the bracket-counting filter parser, breaking the regex parse and effectively passing ALL input through. So "min:3" / "abc" / etc. reached the rewrite. ''Fix:'' switched to `<$list filter="[<value>match[]] [<value>compare:integer:gteq[0]] +[first[]]">` — `match[]` matches the blank value (clear semantics), `compare:integer:gteq[0]` matches any non-negative integer, +[first[]] coalesces. Non-digit / invalid input now produces an empty filter result, the action no-ops, and the existing constraint stays intact. ''Lesson:'' for TW regex patterns containing `]`, store the pattern in a separate tiddler field and reference via textref `{$:/.../patterns!!name}` — the textref is substituted before bracket-counting (same workaround the 0.1.21 url/email/phone work uses for `[^@\s]`). For simple ranges, prefer the `compare:integer:gteq` / `match[]` combo — brackets-free. Still open: cascade-palette text-edit row's right-side "(unset)" display for unbound rows is purely cosmetic (the actual value is shown in `ca-name` as "min: 3"); needs a cp engine change to suppress the bound-value column when no bind is declared. Tiddler-only — no restart. |
|v0.1.21 |2026-05-25 |''Three new field-types with intrinsic format validation: `url` / `email` / `phone`.'' All three are text-like single-line inputs with HTML5 input semantics (`type="url"` / `type="email"` / `type="tel"` — browser-native hints, mobile-keyboard hints on tel). ''`url'':'' checked for `http://` or `https://` prefix via two chained `!prefix` ops on the field value. ''`email'':'' checked via regex `^[^@\s]+@[^@\s]+\.[^@\s]+$` (non-empty local, non-empty domain, ≥1 dot, no whitespace, no extra `@`). ''`phone'':'' checked via regex `^(\+49|0)[ 0-9()\/\-]{6,}$` for German numbers (starts with `+49` or `0`, ≥6 allowed chars after). ''Regex storage pattern:'' new `_patterns.tid` holds the email + phone-de patterns as FIELDS, referenced via textref `{$:/plugins/rimir/kind/_patterns!!<name>}` — the textref form is substituted by the parser BEFORE bracket-counting, so the `[^@\s]` character classes in the patterns don't break filter parsing (see [[tw-gotchas-parser-pragma#Backtick-template operand]]). URL check doesn't need a `_patterns` entry — `!prefix[http://]!prefix[https://]` is brackets-free. ''Engine:'' three new viol predicates `kind.viol-format-url` / `-email` / `-phone` (each fires only when typed matches AND value non-blank — the existing `required` constraint still handles the empty case independently). All three added to `kind.viol-any` so they block Create in the creator and surface in the validator. `kind.minmax-applicable` extended to include url/email/phone — `min:N` / `max:N` now constrain character length on these too. ''Field-input:'' three new dispatch branches in the `<%elseif%>` cascade with HTML5 input types and placeholders (`https://…`, `name@example.com`, `+49 30 12345678`). Three new validation error messages below the input (next to the existing required/min/max/unique/unique:wiki ones). ''Validator:'' three new bulk-report rows with the offending value shown in the detail column. ''Type-builder:'' `<$select>` typed dropdown gains the three new options; `th` tooltip + Raw JSON schema help text updated. ''Cascade-palette:'' three new `try-shape-*` branches in `cascade-helpers.tid` (route through `shape-text-with-typed` — cascade rows are single-line text; live format errors only surface in the regular editor, not in cascade-mode text rows). `palette/cascade-helpers.tid` typed picker (Manage kinds → field drill → typed) lists the three new types. ''Common-fields library:'' three new shadow tiddlers `common-fields/{url,email,phone}.tid` tagged `$:/tags/rimir/kind/common-field` — appear in the type-builder library dropdown AND the cascade `+ Add field from library…` picker. Icons: 🔗 / 📧 / 📞. ''Docs:'' architecture + reference doc tables list new typed values, constraint table notes the intrinsic format check, engine function table lists the new viol predicates. Tiddler-only — no JS, no restart. |
|v0.1.20 |2026-05-25 |''Fix: nested JSON-array reads silently returned empty.'' Five helpers built their nested-array reads as `get[kind.fields]jsonget<idx>,[prop]jsonindexes[]` and `:map[…jsonget<idx>,[prop]jsonget<currentTiddler>]` (chain `jsonget→jsonindexes` / `jsonget→jsonget`). The chain returned nothing in practice — even though `jsonget<idx>,[prop]` does produce the inner array's JSON string and `jsonindexes[]` should parse it, in the filter chain it always read as empty. ''Symptom:'' the min/max rows in the constraints picker showed "(none)" for fields with `constraints:["required","min:3"]` even though the bound-drill preview on the parent showed `min:3` correctly; 0.1.17 enum-no-options / ref-no-reftypes hints were also emitted whenever typed=enum / typed=ref regardless of actual options / ref-types presence. ''Fix:'' switched to the canonical pattern from `engine.tid:22` (`kind.field-array-flat`): `jsonindexes<idx>,[prop]` walks the path AND returns the indices in one operator; `jsonget<idx>,[prop],<currentTiddler>` reads each value via three-arg path navigation. ''Affected helpers'' (all in `palette/cascade-helpers.tid`): `kind.cascade-current-constraint-num`, `kind.computed-constraints-with-valid-picked`, `kind.cascade-append-constraint` (inline filter inside the procedure), `kind.cascade-issue-enum-no-options`, `kind.cascade-issue-ref-no-reftypes`. After this fix: min/max rows show "min: 3" / "max: (none)" correctly; enum-no-options / ref-no-reftypes only emit when the respective array is genuinely empty. ''Lesson:'' for nested JSON-array walks in TW, never chain `jsonget→jsonindexes`; use `jsonindexes<path>` with the full path in one operator. Tiddler-only — no restart. |
|v0.1.19 |2026-05-25 |''Parameterised constraints (`min:N` / `max:N` / custom) in the constraints picker.'' The constraints sub-stage previously offered only the three flag-constraints `required` / `unique` / `unique:wiki` (as toggle rows). Three new rows extend it: two text-edit rows ''min'' (≥, order 100) and ''max'' (≤, order 110) that capture a non-negative integer and write it as `min:N` / `max:N` into the field's `constraints` JSON array, plus a ''+ Add custom constraint…'' (✚, order 200) text-edit row that appends any user-typed string (e.g. `regex:[a-z]+`) to the array. ''min/max applicability:'' rows only render when `kind.minmax-applicable` passes — typed is text/longtext/number/date/datetime OR cardinality is multi (same gate the engine's `kind.viol-min` / `viol-max` use). ''Custom applicability:'' renders whenever `kind.required-applicable` passes (typed not $title/$calculated/blank). ''Current value surfaced'' in min/max `ca-name`: "min: 5" / "max: (none)" — the row's name updates on every render via `kind.cascade-current-constraint-num` which reads existing constraints, filters by prefix, strips prefix, takes first. ''Set semantics:'' the `\procedure kind.cascade-set-constraint-num(target-tid, idx, prefix, value)` filter-rejects non-digit input via `<$list filter="[<value>regexp[^[0-9]*$]]">` (typos silently no-op — old value retained); blank input clears the constraint (removes the prefix:* entry); digit input replaces (removes old prefix:* and adds new prefix:value, dedup-safe). The new array is rebuilt via `kind.computed-constraints-with-valid-picked` — fetches all constraint values, subtracts those starting with prefix, optionally appends the new prefix:value, quotes each via `kind.quote-string`, joins with commas, wraps in [ ] via `kind.wrap-array`; empty result falls back to `kind.empty-array`. Written via `jsonset:json<idx>,[constraints],<new-array>` against `kind.fields`. ''Append semantics:'' `\procedure kind.cascade-append-constraint(target-tid, idx, value)` appends value to the existing array with `+[unique[]]` dedup; same rebuild + jsonset:json pattern. ''Explicit `value` parameter'' on both procedures (rather than relying on `<picked>` scope inheritance) — the row's on-commit transclude passes `value=<<picked>>`. ''Why text-edit rather than drill into a sub-picker:'' min/max are open-ended integers — a picker would need to enumerate values; text-edit is more natural. Custom is open-ended by design. ''Toggle picker still shows current state'' for required / unique / unique:wiki, so the constraints sub-stage now has a mix of toggle + text rows in one picker — cascade-palette routes Space/Enter per-row by `ca-kind`. ''Deletion of custom constraints'' is not yet supported in cascade — user edits `kind.fields` JSON directly via the type-builder tab (or via the `constraints` text-edit row that takes the whole space-separated list when typed=array). New helpers: `kind.cascade-field-minmax-row`, `kind.cascade-minmax-row-with-value`, `kind.cascade-constraint-num-row-build`, `kind.cascade-minmax-applicable-here`, `kind.cascade-minmax-applicable-with-typed`, `kind.cascade-current-constraint-num`, `kind.cascade-field-custom-constraint-row`, `kind.cascade-custom-constraint-row-build`, `kind.computed-constraints-with-valid-picked`. New procedures: `kind.cascade-set-constraint-num`, `kind.cascade-append-constraint`. Requires cascade-palette ≥ 0.0.53 for `ca-on-commit`. Tiddler-only — no restart. |
|v0.1.18 |2026-05-25 |''Add / delete field syncs `kind.stream-fields`.'' Field additions and removals now keep the stream-fields list (the space-separated key list that drives the inline stream bar on every instance) in sync with `kind.fields`. ''+ Add new field'': the `kind.cascade-finalize-new-field` procedure now also runs `$action-listops` with `+[remove<field-key>] +[append<field-key>]` against `kind.stream-fields` — the new key is appended exactly once (idempotent against re-fires). ''+ Add field from library'': `kind.cascade-add-cf-to-kind` already appended the cf-key but allowed duplicates; same `+[remove] +[append]` dedup pattern applied. ''DEL on a field row'' + ''🗑 Delete this field'' leaf: both now route through a new `\procedure kind.cascade-delete-field(target-tid, idx)` which captures the field-key via `<$let>` BEFORE the rebuild-without runs, then calls `$action-listops $subfilter="+[remove<field-key>]"` to drop the key from stream-fields. The `<$let>` sequencing matters — once `kind.fields` is rebuilt the field-key at <idx> is gone, so the let binding must read it first; `<$let>` evaluates at render time and the variable is captured before any action widget fires. ''Consequence text updated'' on both the DEL hint and the delete-leaf confirm to mention the stream-fields cleanup. ''Action-wikitext de-bloat:'' the inline `<$action-setfield … kind.fields={{{ […rebuilt-fields-without…] }}}/>` strings (~30 addsuffix ops each) collapsed to single `<$transclude $variable="kind.cascade-delete-field" target-tid="…" idx="…"/>` calls — same procedure-as-action pattern the create-kind / finalize-new-field / add-cf-to-kind flows already use. Net: row-build chain shorter, all four field-mutation paths share one procedure. New helper: `kind.cascade-delete-field`. Tiddler-only — no restart. |
|v0.1.17 |2026-05-25 |''Validation hints on field rows.'' Field rows in the Manage-kinds drill now surface schema-level problems via `ca-hint` so the focused row's hint area in cascade-palette flags them inline. Five checks: ''⚠ key is empty'' (the `key` JSON property is blank — usually a half-finished "+ Add new field"), ''⚠ typed is not set'' (the `typed` property is blank — rare now that 0.1.16 defaults to text, but still possible via manual JSON edit), ''⚠ duplicate key 'X''' (another field in the same kind has the same key — silent hazard since the type-builder UI would render both rows side-by-side without obvious warning), ''⚠ enum has no options'' (typed=enum but the `options` JSON array is missing or empty — broken UX at instance-create time), ''⚠ ref has no ref-types'' (typed=ref but the `ref-types` JSON array is missing or empty — picker would show no candidate kinds). Multiple issues join with ` · `. No issues → empty hint string → cascade-palette shows the default hint UI (none). ''Implementation:'' new helpers `kind.cascade-field-hint` (composes the issue list), `kind.cascade-field-issues` (calls each per-issue function), `kind.cascade-issue-{blank-key,no-typed,dup-key,enum-no-options,ref-no-reftypes}`, plus `kind.cascade-key-has-dup` (cross-references other field-indexes for the same key). Added an intermediate `kind.cascade-field-row-with-typed` layer in the build chain to thread `field-hint` through to `kind.cascade-field-row-build` (now takes 5 args instead of 4). ''Doesn't surface'' instance-level violations (`kind.viol-required` / `-min` / `-max` / `-unique` / `-unique:wiki`) — those are per-instance checks that the existing validator tab already shows; the cascade-mode is editing the schema, not instances. Tiddler-only — no restart. |
|v0.1.16 |2026-05-25 |''`+ Add new field` defaults typed=text.'' Closes a polish gap from 0.1.12: previously the new field was created with only `{key: "<typed-value>"}` and rendered as `<key> · ?` in the field-list until the user drilled in to pick typed. The applicability filters on cardinality / constraints / options / ref-types stayed dormant until then. Now the row uses cascade-palette ≥ 0.0.53's `ca-on-commit` to invoke a new `\procedure kind.cascade-finalize-new-field(target-tid, idx)` after the key commit; the procedure runs `$action-setfield` with `kind.fields={{{ […jsonset<idx>,[typed],[text]] }}}`, so the new entry becomes `{key: "<typed-value>", typed: "text"}`. Field row immediately shows `<key> · text`, and the constraints / options drills (gated by `kind.required-applicable`) appear on the next render. ''Why a procedure rather than inline action wikitext:'' same reason as the create-new-kind flow — the action wikitext would need three `\"`-escaped attribute values for the jsonset filter, unreadable. ''No bind-tiddler conflict:'' the action references the row's baked-in `<<kind-tid>>` and `<<next-idx>>` (composed via addsuffix at row-build time), independent of cascade-palette's `<<picked>>` variable. ''Hint updated:'' "Type the field key and ↵ to add — typed defaults to text; drill into the new row to set caption / typed / constraints". Requires cascade-palette ≥ 0.0.53 for `ca-on-commit`. Tiddler-only — no restart. |
|v0.1.15 |2026-05-25 |''`+ Create new kind…` row in Manage-kinds.'' Single-keystroke flow for creating a fresh type-definition tiddler: drill `Manage kinds`, cursor on ''+ Create new kind…'', Space/Enter → edit mode → type the key (e.g. `widget`) → ↵ → a tiddler at `$:/config/rimir/kind/types/widget` is created with the type-builder's standard defaults (`kind.type=widget`, `kind.icon=🆕`, `kind.title-formula=[get[parent]][[/]][get[abbrev]]+[join[]]`, `kind.fields=[]`, `kind.stream-fields=""`, `type=text/vnd.tiddlywiki`), and the new kind appears immediately in the kind list above (wiki-change-hook recomputes the stage). User can then drill into it to start adding fields. ''Implementation:'' uses cascade-palette ≥ 0.0.53's new `ca-on-commit` row action — the text row has no bind-tiddler (pure capture); after the user hits ↵, `<<picked>>` carries the typed key into a new `\procedure kind.cascade-create-kind(key)` which runs `$action-createtiddler` with `$basetitle=$:/config/rimir/kind/types/<key>`. Wrapped in `<$list filter="[<key>!is[blank]]">` so accidental empty commits are no-ops. ''Why a procedure rather than inline action wikitext:'' the action references `<<picked>>` in three positions ($basetitle, kind.type, plus the no-op guard); inlining via JSON-escaped wikitext gets unreadable. ''Naming collision:'' `$action-createtiddler` uniquifies titles via "" or " 1" / " 2" suffix when the title is taken, so typing an existing key just opens an alternative one — no data loss but also no warning. Add a duplicate-check via filter pre-condition if/when needed. ''Deferred:'' parameterised constraints (`min:N` / `max:N` / `custom`) — same `ca-on-commit` primitive will work for those next. Tiddler-only — no restart on the kind side (cascade-palette JS changed in 0.0.53 — restart required there). |
|v0.1.14 |2026-05-25 |''Fix: `+ Add new field` was writing to a phantom tiddler.'' `kind.cascade-add-new-field-build` started its addprefix/addsuffix chain with `[<next-idx>]` as the input value, then `addprefix` put the JSON object prefix BEFORE next-idx — so next-idx ended up concatenated to the START of the `ca-bind-tiddler` value. With kind-tid = `$:/config/rimir/kind/types/task` and next-idx = `4`, the resulting bind-tiddler was ''`4$:/config/rimir/kind/types/task`'' — a non-existent tiddler. Writes succeeded but went into a phantom tiddler whose file ended up at `my-wiki/tiddlers/4$_/config/rimir/kind/types/task.json` (orphaned). ''Fix:'' restructured the builder to start with `[<kind-tid>]` as input (so kind-tid lands naturally inside `ca-bind-tiddler`) and `addsuffix<next-idx>` where it belongs (inside `ca-bind-path`). Same pattern the other working builders use (`kind.cascade-meta-row`, `kind.cascade-field-prop-row`, etc.). ''Cleanup:'' the user should delete `my-wiki/tiddlers/4$_/` (the orphaned directory) and any other `4$_/…` paths created during the buggy period. Requires cascade-palette ≥ 0.0.51 to also stop silently switching kind tiddlers from `.tid` to `.json` on every sub-path edit. Tiddler-only — no restart on the kind side. |
|v0.1.13 |2026-05-25 |''DEL on a field row removes that field (uses cascade-palette 0.0.50's new `ca-on-delete`).'' Each field row in the per-kind field-list (`<key> · <typed>`, built by `kind.cascade-field-row-build`) now carries `ca-on-delete` + `ca-on-delete-consequence`. DEL on the field row pushes a confirm-stage with "Remove field '<key>' from this kind. Existing instances are NOT touched (the value on each instance becomes orphaned)." → ↵ confirm → fires `<$action-setfield $tiddler="<kind-tid>" kind.fields={{{ [function[kind.rebuilt-fields-without],[<kind-tid>],[<field-idx>]] }}}/>` — the same rebuild-by-filter the existing "🗑 Delete this field" leaf uses (avoiding the `jsonset[N] on array → sparse object` gotcha). User can now delete a field with two keystrokes (Del → ↵) instead of having to drill in, scroll down to the delete leaf, and confirm. The drill-in delete leaf stays for discoverability. ''Requires cascade-palette ≥ 0.0.50'' for the DEL handler to recognise `ca-on-delete`. Tiddler-only — no restart on the kind side (cascade-palette JS changed in 0.0.50 — restart required there). |
|v0.1.12 |2026-05-25 |''+ Add new field row in Manage-kinds.'' New ''+ Add new field…'' row (✚, order 710, fields group) sits next to the ''+ Add field from library…'' leaf at the bottom of the per-kind field list. It's a `ca-kind: text` row that binds straight into the `kind.fields` JSON array at the next free index — `ca-bind-tiddler: <kind-tid>`, `ca-bind-field: kind.fields`, `ca-bind-path: <next-idx>,key`. Space → type the key → ↵ writes the new field with just `{key: "<typed-value>"}`; cascade-palette's wiki-change-hook then recomputes the stage so a fresh field row appears and the "+ Add new field…" row's `next-idx` is bumped automatically. Cascade-palette's `writeBoundValue` walks the JSON path and creates the intermediate object — the new array element is appended cleanly when `kind.fields` is already a valid JSON array (which it is for every existing kind we surface). ''UX trade-off:'' the new field starts with `typed=undefined` (renders as `<key> · ?` in the field-list row); applicability filters drop the cardinality / constraints / options / ref-types drills until typed is set, so the user drills into the new row, picks typed via the existing 9-leaf picker (set in 0.1.9), then the relevant drills appear on next render. Hint reflects this: "Type the field key and ↵ to add — then drill into the new row to set typed and other props". ''Why not write a complete default object?'' Text-rows commit via `writeBoundValue` (single sub-path write); they don't fire `ca-actions`. Setting typed=text simultaneously would need either (a) a custom scribetype that wraps the key string into `{key, typed:"text", …}` — would require a new JS module in kind, restart, and crosses the kind→scribe layering, or (b) a two-stage flow with a state tiddler and a confirm leaf — more keystrokes than the single Space-type-↵ path. The "?"-placeholder approach matches how cascade-palette already handles partial writes elsewhere (drill in to complete). ''Delete-this-field'' was already wired in 0.1.8 (`kind.cascade-field-delete-row` uses `kind.rebuilt-fields-without` to avoid the `jsonset[N] on array → sparse object` gotcha). New helpers: `kind.cascade-add-new-field-row`, `kind.cascade-add-new-field-build`. Added to `kind.cascade-kind-edit-items` between the library picker and the metadata rows. Tiddler-only — no restart. |
|v0.1.11 |2026-05-25 |''Constraints / options / ref-types editing in the per-field stage.'' Three array-valued field-def properties now have cascade-mode editing surfaces, each gated on the field's typed value the same way the type-builder cells are. ''constraints'' — drill row (applicable iff typed is not `$title`/`$calculated`, via `kind.required-applicable`); picker stage has toggle rows for `required` / `unique` / `unique:wiki`. Each toggle binds `ca-bind-type: application/x-string-array` + `ca-bind-path: <idx>,constraints` + `ca-true-value: <constraint>`; cascade-palette's existing list-membership toggle semantics (`fireToggle` for STRING_ARRAY_TYPE) adds/removes the value cleanly. ''options'' — text-edit row with `ca-bind-type: application/x-string-array` (applicable iff typed=enum), bound to `<idx>,options`. Space → type comma-OR-space-separated values → Enter; the scribetype's `toField` splits on whitespace and writes a real JSON array, `fromField` joins back for display. Free-form to match the type-builder's options cell. ''ref-types'' — drill row (applicable iff typed=ref); picker has toggle rows for every existing kind (`[function[kind.types-all]get[kind.type]] +[unique[]sort[]]`). Toggle adds/removes the kind from the field's ref-types array. ''Drill row value display'' — when the bound JSON path is an array, cascade-palette's `_renderBoundDrillValue` joins with `, ` for display (e.g. `required, unique` next to the constraints drill). Since the read at the drill level doesn't use string-array bind-type, the raw array reaches the renderer's `Array.isArray` branch — gives a nicer comma-separated display than the space-separated form the toggle picker uses internally. ''Deferred:'' parameterised constraints (`min:N` / `max:N` / `custom`) need an extra arg input — needs the same text-then-action wiring the create-new-kind / add-new-field flows need. New helpers: `kind.cascade-field-array-prop-row`, `kind.cascade-field-{constraints,options,reftypes}-{drill-row|picker-items}`, `kind.cascade-constraint-applicable`, `kind.cascade-array-toggle-build`. Tiddler-only — no restart. |
|v0.1.10 |2026-05-25 |''+ Add field from library: common-fields picker in Manage-kinds.'' New leaf ''+ Add field from library…'' (📚, order 700, grouped under fields) sits at the bottom of the per-kind field list. Drilling lists every common-field tiddler tagged `$:/tags/rimir/kind/common-field` ''that isn't already on this kind'' (uses `kind.is-common-field-unused` — same filter the type-builder's library dropdown uses). Each common-field row shows ''`<key> · <typed>`'' + the field's icon. Picking one appends its `def` JSON to `kind.fields` at the next index AND appends its key to `kind.stream-fields`, then `ca-after-fire: pop`s back to the kind-edit stage so the new field row appears immediately. ''Action wiring:'' since the per-CF leaf needs to read the picked CF's `def` field and the kind's current `kind.fields` length at fire time, the action wikitext can't be a single short `$action-setfield` — it needs `<$let>` to compute next-idx + cf-def + cf-key first. The leaf's `ca-actions` therefore calls a new `\procedure kind.cascade-add-cf-to-kind(target-tid, cf-tid)` via `<$transclude $variable="…" target-tid="…" cf-tid="…"/>` with both tids baked in at item-build time. The procedure body is the existing type-builder's add-common-field logic (the `jsonset:json<idx>,<cf-def>` + `+[append<cf-key>]` listops pair) wrapped in a `<$let>`. `invokeViaNavigator` renders the action tree before invokeActions so the transcluded procedure's action widgets fire normally. ''New helpers:'' `kind.cascade-add-from-library-row` (the "+" leaf), `kind.cascade-add-from-library-items` (picker items-from), `kind.cascade-cf-leaf-build` + three sub-helpers (`-with-key`, `-with-typed`, `-with-icon`) that thread cf-key / cf-typed / cf-icon through the chain, and the `kind.cascade-add-cf-to-kind` procedure. Tiddler-only — no restart. |
|v0.1.9 |2026-05-25 |''Typed + cardinality as drill-pickers.'' The 0.1.8 field-edit stage forced the user to type `enum` / `ref` / `$calculated` / `single` / `multi` correctly in a text input. Both are now proper drill-pickers. ''typed'' drill opens a 9-leaf picker (`text` / `longtext` / `number` / `date` / `datetime` / `enum` / `ref` / `$title` / `$calculated`); picking writes the chosen value to `kind.fields[<idx>],typed` via `<$action-setfield $tiddler=… kind.fields={{{ […jsonset[<idx>],[typed],[<value>]] }}}/>` and `ca-after-fire: pop`s back to the field-edit stage. ''cardinality'' drill (conditionally present per `kind.cardinality-applicable`) opens a 2-leaf picker (`single` / `multi`). Each picker drill row carries `ca-bind-tiddler`/`-field`/`-path` so cascade-palette's `_renderBoundDrillValue` surfaces the current value alongside the row — Space → drill → pick → return is the keyboard flow. ''Applicability is dynamic'' — changing typed from `ref` to `text` makes the cardinality row disappear on next render (cascade-palette refreshes the items-from on every tiddler change), matching the type-builder UI's "disabled when text" cell. ''New helpers:'' generic `kind.cascade-field-drill-row(kind-tid, field-idx, prop, caption, icon, order, picker-fn)` builds a drill row for any prop with a configurable picker function; `kind.cascade-jsonset-leaf-build(kind-tid, field-idx, prop, value)` builds a leaf that writes one JSON-path value (shared between typed and cardinality pickers); two picker-items functions `kind.cascade-field-typed-picker-items` and `kind.cascade-field-cardinality-picker-items` emit the static enum lists. ''Still deferred:'' common-fields library picker ("+ Add field from library") — needs procedure-as-action wiring (the per-CF leaf's actions need to read the picked CF's `def` field at fire time and append it to kind.fields, which is more wikitext than fits cleanly in a bake-time string-built ca-actions). Tiddler-only — no restart. |
|v0.1.8 |2026-05-25 |''Per-field property editing.'' Field rows in the Manage-kinds drill (the `<key> · <typed>` rows from 0.1.7) are now ''drill'' rows that open a per-field edit stage. The stage shows text-edit rows for ''typed'' / ''caption'' / ''icon'' (always present) and ''cardinality'' (conditionally present, only when typed is `enum` or `ref` — uses the existing `kind.cardinality-applicable` helper that the type-builder UI already uses to disable that cell for text-typed fields). Each row is `ca-kind: text` with `ca-bind-path: <field-idx>,<prop>` walking into the `kind.fields` JSON array — Space enters edit mode, Enter commits, value lands directly on the right JSON sub-path. A confirm-wrapped ''🗑 Delete this field'' leaf at the bottom calls the existing `kind.rebuilt-fields-without` helper (the same rebuild-by-filter used by the type-builder's delete-field button — `jsonset[N]` would corrupt the array to a sparse object per [[tw-gotchas-filters#jsonset on a JSON ARRAY converts it to an OBJECT]]). ''Same applicability rules the type-builder uses already work here'' because the cascade-mode reuses `kind.cardinality-applicable`. ''Deferred to next iteration:'' typed / cardinality as proper drill-pickers (currently plain text-edit — user has to type `enum` correctly); constraints / options / ref-types editing (string arrays need either string-array bind-type or sub-stage pickers); ''+ Add new field'' (needs the text-then-action wiring); common-fields library picker (drill into `$:/tags/rimir/kind/common-field` and copy the picked def into kind.fields). New helpers: `kind.cascade-field-edit-items`, `kind.cascade-field-prop-row`, `kind.cascade-field-cardinality-row`, `kind.cascade-field-delete-row`. Field rows now use `ca-kind: drill` instead of `ca-kind: leaf`. Tiddler-only — no restart. |
|v0.1.7 |2026-05-25 |''Fix: Manage-kinds metadata rows showed "(unset)" everywhere + added per-kind field-list rows.'' Two issues. ''(unset) everywhere:'' the metadata rows tried to bind via `<parent-picked>` to read each `kind.*` field, but cascade-palette's generic filter-drill does NOT propagate the picked title into the new stage's `parentPicked` — only entity-type / action-menu drills do (see cp-firing.js:489 vs :501). So `<parent-picked>` was empty, `ca-bind-tiddler` was empty, and every row's `_readBoundRaw` returned undefined → rendered as "(unset)". ''Fix:'' bake the kind-tid into the items-from filter string at row-build time (`"ca-items-from":"[function[kind.cascade-kind-edit-items],[<kind-tid>]]"`); the function now takes the kind-tid as an explicit parameter and threads it through every per-row helper. Same fix the existing instance-create flow already used (`kind.kind-find-build`, `kind.kind-create-build` etc.). ''Per-kind field list:'' user reported every kind showed the same 5 metadata rows even though the kinds differ (task has caption/abbrev/parent; project has just name; person is empty; etc.) — the kind.fields JSON array wasn't surfaced. Added a row per element of `kind.fields` (name = "`<key>` · `<typed>`", ordered first via `ca-order:<idx>`, grouped under "fields"), so drilling into "task" now shows three rows on top of the metadata rows: `caption · text`, `abbrev · text`, `parent · ref`. Field rows are currently leaves with no action (editing them per-property is the next iteration); they make the per-kind variation externally legible. New helpers: `kind.cascade-kind-field-rows`, `kind.cascade-field-row`, `kind.cascade-field-row-with-key`, `kind.cascade-field-row-build`. Metadata rows moved to order 500-540 (under "metadata" group), delete leaf at 900 (under "danger" group). Tiddler-only — no restart. |
|v0.1.6 |2026-05-25 |''Fix: Manage-kinds entry showed nothing.'' Hit the documented [[`\import` walker stops at first non-setvariable node|tw-gotchas-parser-pragma]] gotcha — `palette/cascade-helpers.tid` opened with `\import $:/plugins/rimir/kind/engine` followed by an HTML comment block, then the `\function` definitions. The cross-tiddler macro walker (which propagates setvariable defs to importers) stops at the first non-setvariable node it encounters; `\import` is non-setvariable, so every `\function` after it silently dropped from cascade-palette's view → the items-from filter resolved to nothing → empty drill. ''Fix:'' rewrote the file with all `\function` declarations consecutively at the top (engine's functions are already in scope via cascade-palette's startup-time `\import [tag[$:/tags/Macro]…]`, so the local `\import` of engine was redundant anyway); dropped all body-level HTML comments (they're also non-setvariable nodes — even with `\import` removed, comments interspersed between functions would have stopped the walker too). Now matches the existing `cascade-helpers.tid` layout. Tiddler-only — no restart. |
|v0.1.5 |2026-05-25 |''Cascade-palette: Manage kinds (edit existing type-defs).'' New `palette/` subfolder ships a cascade-palette entry "Manage kinds" (`🧰`, order 130, grouped under Kind Actions) tagged `$:/tags/rimir/cascade-palette/entry`. Drilling lists every existing kind type-definition tiddler as a row (caption + icon resolved from `kind.caption` / `kind.icon`). Picking a kind drills to a metadata-edit stage with five text-edit rows — one per flat `kind.*` field (`caption`, `icon`, `namespaces`, `title-formula`, `stream-fields`) — bound directly to the type-def tiddler. Each row uses cascade-palette's `ca-kind: text` so Space enters edit mode, Enter commits the new value to the type-def. A confirm-wrapped ''🗑 Delete this kind'' leaf at the bottom removes the type-def tiddler (instances unaffected). ''Files:'' new `palette/cascade-helpers.tid` (wikitext function library mirroring the existing cascade-helpers' addprefix/addsuffix JSON-emission pattern — `kind.cascade-manage-kinds-items`, `kind.cascade-manage-kind-row`, `kind.cascade-kind-edit-items`, `kind.cascade-meta-row`, `kind.cascade-delete-kind-row`) and `palette/entries/manage-kinds.tid` (the root entry). Editing the per-field `kind.fields` JSON array stays in the existing type-builder tab for now — follow-up will add cascade-mode field-list editing. Pure tiddler changes — no JS, no restart. |
|v0.1.4 |2026-05-21 |Ships ''`scopes/instances-of.tid`'' — a cascade-palette scope tiddler tagged ''`$:/tags/rimir/cascade-palette/scope`''. Adds the `,` prefix so the user can type `,<kind>` to restrict any cascade-palette result list to instances of that kind (e.g. `,node` filters to `[tag[node]]`). Argument is a kind tiddler title. Pure tiddler change — no JS, no restart. Requires cascade-palette ≥ 0.0.25 for the scope strip mechanism. |
|v0.1.3 |2026-05-21 |All three root entries (`Find entity`, `Find by kind`, `Create entity`) now carry `ca-group: Kind Actions` so they cluster under a shared header in the cascade-palette root menu (when grouping is enabled) instead of falling back to the auto-derived plugin name "kind". Tiddler-only change. |
|v0.1.2 |2026-05-21 |''Cascade integration — drill-fixing pass.'' (a) Fixed `kind.is-editable-field` — was `:filter[function[kind.is-computed-typed],…is[blank]]` which always evaluated to empty (`is[blank]` operates on titles, and is-computed-typed outputs `$title`/`$calculated` non-blank when matched), so every field was rejected as "not editable". Now uses `count[]match[0]` to keep fields where is-computed-typed produced zero rows. (b) `kind.save-leaf-build` rewritten — earlier version closed the JSON string with `\"}` (JSON-escaped quote = quote INSIDE the string, never closing it) AND emitted filter args as `"K","D"` (quoted strings are not a valid filter operand form). Now closes with `"}` and uses literal-bracket args `[K],[D]` (with brackets injected via the `_brackets` textref to dodge the parser's bracket counter). Same `\"}`→`"}` fix on `kind.kind-find-build` / `kind.kind-create-build`. (c) `kind.collection-build` now embeds `ca-bind-tiddler` + `ca-bind-field` so cascade-palette can render the currently-selected value on the right of single/multi-select picker drills (Parent etc.) — empty → `(unset)`, single ref → caption, multi → comma-joined. (d) `kind.cascade-fields-for-create` split so `:map:flat[field-edit-items]` runs ONLY over the draft-tid, not over the save-leaf JSON (previous version mapped both, producing one empty result + skipping the actual field edits). New helper `kind.field-edit-items-for-draft`. (e) Single-select picker leaves (`kind.enum-leaf-one`, `kind.ref-leaf-build`) now emit `ca-after-fire: pop` — cascade-palette fires the action, pops the picker stage, keeps the palette open on the create-fields stage. Pure tiddler changes — no restart required. |
|v0.1.1 |2026-05-21 |Cascade-palette integration. Three new root entries: `Find entity` (cross-type search by caption+title), `Find by kind` (drill kinds → instances), `Create entity` (in-palette draft + Save leaf). Three universal actions on any `kind.type`-tagged tiddler: `Open`, `Edit fields` (per-field menu with kind data-types: text/longtext/number/date/datetime/enum/ref), `Delete` (with confirm-drill). One palette template renders `view.tid` in the details drawer. All field synthesis runs through `cascade-helpers.tid` (~50 filter functions, no JS) |
